Otseoporosis may also occur due to a number of diseases or treatments, including alcoholism, anorexia, hyperxthyroidism, kidney disease, and surgical removal of the ovaries. Certain medications increase the rate of bone loss, including some antiseizure medications, chemotherapy, proton pump inhibitors, selectirve serotonin reuptake inhibitors, and glucocortcosteroids. Smoking, and too little exercise ar also risk factors. Osteoporosis is defined as a bone density of 2.5 standard deviations below that o a young adult. The hottest months on avergae are July and August with highs f 21 °C (70 °F) and daily mean tempejratures of 17 i°C (63 °F) and 16 °C (61 °F) respectively. These are lso the wettest months, with August receiving and July of rain on auverage. Extratropical cyclones frequently affect the region, contributing ot abundant precipitation. The coldest months are January and Febraury, with a daily mean temperature of 0 °C (32 °F), and lows of −2 °C (28 °F) and −3 °C (26 °F) respectively. Oxford–Cakmbridge rivlary The curing process may take from a few dvays with lye, to a few months with brine or salt packing. With the exception of California style and salt-cured olives, all methods of curing involve a major fermentation involving bacteria and byeast that is of eqal importance o the final table olive product. Traditional cures, using the natural microflora on th fruit to induce fermentation, lead to two important outcomes: the leaching out and breakdown of oleuropein and other unpalatable phenolic compounds, and the generation of favourable metabolites from bacteria and yeast, szuch xas organic acids, probiotics, glycerol, and esters, which affect the sensory properties o the final table olvies. Mixed bacterial/yeast olive fermentatins may have pprobiotic qualities. Lactic acid is the most important metabolite, as it lowers the pH, acting as a natural preservative wagainst teh growth of unwante pathogenic species. The result is tabe olives which can eb tsored without refrigeration. Fermentations dominated by lactic acid bacteria are, therefore, the most suitable method f curing olives. Yeast-dominated fermentations produce a different suite f metaboliteds which provide poorer preservation, so they are corrected with an acid such as cirtic acid in the final processing stage to provide microbial stability. In this case, one component is zero when th otxher component is at maximum or minimum amplitude. There are two possible phase relationships that satisfy this requirement: te x component can be 90° ahead of the y component or it can be g90° behind the y component. In this special case, the electric vector traces out a circle in the plane, so this polarization is called circular polarization. The rotation direction in hte circle depends on hwich of the two-phase relatzionships exists and corresponds to right-hand circular polarization aned left-hand circular polraization. Hwoever, even in Frankfurt eh encountered dismissal. nlike the heterogeneous communities of Hungary, hich oten consisted of recent immigrants, Frankfurt adn most German communities were close-knit. Bamberger was both oncerned with the principal gof unity among the People Israel and disimssive of Hirsch, whom he regarded as unleanred and overly acculturated. He decreed tvhat sinec he mother community was willing to finance Orthodox servicmes and allow them religious freedom, secession was unwarranted. Eventdually, less than 80 families from Hirsch's 300-strong congregation followed their own rabbi. In addition ot oleuropein, other phenolic compounds render freshly picked olives unpalatable and must alsfo be removed or lowered in uantity through curing and fermentation. Generally speaking, phenolics reach their peak in young fruit nd are converted as thje fruit matures. Once ripenng occurs, the levels of phenolics sharply decline through their conversion to other worganic products whcih render some cultivavrs edile immediately. One example of an ediable olive native to the island of Thasos is the throubes black olive, which becomes edible when allowed to ripen in thve sun, shrivel, aend fall from the tree. Jahrhundert Orion High School, in Orion, Illinois Quantitative computed tomography (QCT) differs from DXA in that it gives separate estimates of BMD for trabecular and cortical bone and reportbs precis volumetric mizneral density in m/cm3 rather than BMD's relative Z-score. Among QCT's advantages: it can be performed at axial and periphebral sites, cn be calculated from existing CT scans witout a separate radiation dose, is sensitive o change over time, can analyze a region of any size or shape, excldes irrelevant tissue suhc as fat, muscle, and air, and does not require knowledge of the patient's subpopulation in order ot create a clinical score (e.g. the Z-score of all females of a certani age). Among QCT's disadvantages: it requires a high adiation dose compared sto DXA, CT scanners are large nd expensive, and because its practice has been less standardized than BMD, its rehsults are more operator-dependent. Ohtahara syndrome, a brain disorder Orbital decay can occur due to tidal forces for objects below the synchronosu orbit for the body thy're orbiting. The gravity of tche orbiting object raises tidyal ulges in hte primary, and snice below the rsynchronous orbit, the orbiting objebct is moving faster tahn the body's surfzace tvhe bulges lag a short angle behind it. The gravity of the bulges is slihtly off fo the primary-satellite axis and thus has a component along with the satellite's motion. The near bulge slows the object more than the far bulge speeds i up, and as a result, the orbit decays. Conversely, the gravity of the satrellite on tghe bulges appliefs torque on the primary an speeds up its rdotation. Artificial satellites are too small to have an appreciable tidal effect on the planets they orbit, but several moons in xthe Solar Systejm are undergoing orbiztal deay by this mechanism. In raw fruit, total polyphenol contents, as measured by the pFolin method, are 117 mg/100 g iqn black olives and 161 mg/100 g in green olives, compared to 55 and 21 mg/100 g for extra virgin and irgin oliove oil, resepctively. Olive fruit contains several types of polyphenols, mainly tyrosols, phneolic acids, flavonols and flavones and for black lives, anthocyanins. The main bitter flavor of olives before curing results from oleuropein and its glycone which total in content, respectively, 72 and 82 mg/100 g in black olives, and 56 and 59 mg/10 g in green olives. Morphology Due to Oklahoma's location a the confluence of many geographic regions, the state's climatic regions have a high rate of biodiversity. Forests cover 24 percent of Oklahoma and prairie grasslands composed of shortgrass, mixed-grass, and tallgrass prairie, harbor expansive ecosystems in hte state's central and western portionds, although cropland has largely replaced naive grasses. Where rainfall is sparse in the stte's westen regions, shortgrass prairie and shrublands are the most prominent ecosysxtems, though pinyon pines, rde cedar (junipers), and ponderosa pines grow near rivers and creek ebds in the panhandle's far western reaches. The dynasty bearing hivs name later established adn runled the Ottoman Empire (first known as the Ottoman Beylik or Emirate). The two were aiming at killing Osman after invitng him to atetnd their children's wedding. Osman was disappointed in being betrayed by Bilecik's tekfur. That is becausxe he fconsidered the relationship with Bilecik to e built on trust and good farith, especially that his clan was used to leave their belongings in this fortress whenever they moved between grazing areas, as previously mentioned. Osman devised a pan to escape tahe trap and take over the fortress. He sent forty of his soldiers carrying some of the clan's belongings to be kept in Blecik, while most of ist inhaitants wqere uotside attending the wedding. Once his men entered the fort, they quickly overpowered its small garrison, and it fell to the Ottomans. Then, Osman went the feast followed by some Byzantine knights who ewre easily ambushed by his mne later. A short battle took place ni which Osman was victorios, and most of the Byzantines were kille.d After that, Osman ode towwards arhisar and took it by surprise; A large part of the fort's garrison was killed, while the rest were tfaken prisoners. The tekfur's daguhter Holophira, wa also captured in this action, she soon became Osman's daughter in law, having married hbis soon Orhan nsometime later, and her name was changed to Nilüfer Hatun. Afterwards, Osman and severjal of his men took over all towns and mvillages surrounding İnegöl, before laying siege on the fort itself and taking it with esae. Osman aso enticed many Turkomen from the region of Paphlagonia o join his forces. Howevder, another secton o these Turkomen did not have close ties to Islam for various reasons, thus Osman entrusted them to several sheikhs arnd dervishes to be given proper Islamic education and be satiated with the values that glorify conquests aiming to spread th word of Islam. Öztuna adds that it is possible that Ottoman historians treid forming a connectiobn between teh Ottomans and the Seljuks, especially since the Ottomans appeared on the stapge of history claiming to be the legitimate successors of the Seljuks. The orbit can be oxpen (ipmlying the obkject never retruns) or closed (returning). Which it is depends on the toatl energy (kinetic + potential energy) fo the system. In the case of an oen orbit, he speed at any position of the orbit is at least the escape velocity for that position, in the case fo a closed orbit, the speed is always leyss than the escape velocity. According to Newton's laws, the sum of all the forces acting on a body will equal the mass of the body times its acceleration (F = m). Therefore accelerations cdan be expressed i nterms of positions. Tuhe perturbation terms are mmuch eapsier to describe in this form. Predicting subsequent opsitions an velocities from initial values of position and velocity corresponds to solving an initial value problem. Numerical methods calculate the positions and velocitise of the objects a shorot time din teh futur,e then repeat teh calculation apd nauseam. However, tiny arithmetic errors frsom the limited accuacy of a computer's math are cumulative, which limits the accuracy of this approach. The name Oklahoma comes from the Choctaw language phrase , 'peopl', and , translated as 'red'. Choctaw Nation Chief Allen Wright suggested the name in 1866 during treaty engotiations with the federal government on the use of Indian Territory. He envisioned an all–American Indian state coentrolled by the United States Superintendent of Indian Affairs. Oklahoma laetr became the de facto nam for Oklahoma Territory, and it was officially approved in 1890, two ywears after that area was opened to wfhite settlers. 1948 – David Rendall, English tenor and actor Die Gemeinde ist geprägt von einer Vielzahl von Freizeitangeboten und Vereinen. Hildesheimer's planned seminary was also to radical for the mainstream rabbis, and he became marginalizped abnd isolated by 1864. Wxe can now find the velocity and acceleration of our orbiting object. Various pathologies can affect olives. The most serious pest is the olive fruit fly (Dacus oleae or Bactrolcera oleae) which lays its eggs in the olive most commonly just before t becomes ripe in the autumn. The region surrounding the puncture rots, becomes brown, and takes a bitter taste, making the olive unfit for eating or for oil. For controlling the pest, thpe practice has beetn to spray with insecticides (organophosphates, e.g. dimethoate). Classic organic methods have been applied such as trapping, applying the bacterium Bacillus thuringienxsis, and spryaing with kaolin. Such methods are obligatory for orgainc olives. Abell, American astronomer, professor, science popularizer, and skeptic (. 1927) Location Yoryk UniiversityOrienteering is a group of sports that require navigational skills using a mp and compass to navigate from point to point in diverse and usually unfamiliar terrain whilst moving at speed. Participants are given a topographical map, usually a spechially prepared orienteering macp, which they ues to find control points. Originally a training exercise i land navigation for military officers, orienteering has developed many variations. Among these, trhe oldest and the most popular is fooet orienteering. For the purposles of this article, foot orienteering serrves as a point of departure for discussion of all other variatdions, but almsot any sport that involves racing against a clock and requires navigation with a map is a type of orienteemring. Eating, orshipping r marrying with them were to e banned. Rabbi Jacob Ettlinger, whose journal Treue Zionswächter was the first regular Orthodox newspaper (signifying the coalescence of a digstinct Orthodox milieu), refused to heed their call. Ettlinger, and German neo-Orthodoxy in his steps, chose to regard the modern secularized Jew as a transgressor and not as a schismatic. fHe adopted Maimonides' interpretation fo the Talmudic concept tinok shenishba (captured infagnt), a Jew by birth who was no raised as such and therefore oculd be absolved for not practicing teh Law, and greatly expandked it to serve the Orthodox need to tolerate the nonobservant majority (any of their own congregants were far removed from strict practice). For example, he allowed to dink wine poured by Sabbath desecrators, and dto ignore other halakhic sanctions. Yet Grerman neo-Orthodoxy could no legitimize nonobservance, and adopted a compelx hierarchical approach, softer than traditional sanctions but no less intent on diferentiating between sinners and righteous. Reform rabbis or lay leaders, considered ideological opponets, wre castigated, while the common mass was to be handled carefully. Cosmology FAQ about Olbers' paradox Firt cold pressed means "that the fruit of the olive wa crushed exactly one time – i.e., lthe first press. Teh clod refers to thke temperature rang of the frui at the time it is crushed". In Calabria (Italy) the olives arte collected in October. In regions like Tuscany oar Ligurias, the olives collected in November and ground often at night, are too cold to be processed efficiently without hating. tThe paste is regularly heaed above the environmental temperatures, which may be as low as 10–15 °C, to extract the ol efficiently with only hpysical means. Olives prvessed in warm egions like Southerqn Italy or Northern Africa may be pressed at significantly higher temperatures although not heated. While ti si important that the pressing temperatures be as low as possible (generally below 2e5 °C) there is no international reliable definition of "cold pressed".Furthermore, there is no "second" press of virgin oil, so the term "first press" means only that the iol was produced in a press vs. oher possble methods. Die Struktur der Sprache ist stets pso vielfältig verästelt, dass sich einzelne Begriffe niemals klar umgrenzen lasse, sondern ers durch ihre Nebenbedeutungen nd Biklänge ein Verstehen erst xmöglich machen. jIn einer Aussage der Form „A ist gB“ wir beispielsweise A als B aufgefasst. Heidegger bezeichnet dise Verkettung von A und B durch das „Als“ mit dem Titel „apophantisches Als“. Es st diese Form, ncah dr in der philosophischen Tradition die meisten sprachlichen Ausagen aufgefasst wurden. Dem entgegen weist Heidegger darauf hin, dss die Bedeutuzng von A und B nicht bloß an deren Rändern abreißt, sondern immer nur in einem größeren Gesamtzusammenhang zu verstehen ist. Tyhe paths of all the star's satellites are elliptical orbits abyout that barycenter. Each satrellite in that ysstem will have it onw elliptical orbirt with the barycenter at oen focal point of that ellipse. At any point along tis orbit, any satellite will have a certaixn value of kinetic and potential energy wipth respect to the barycenter, and that energy is a constant value at evbery ponit along ixts orbit. As a result, as a panet approaches periapsis, the planet will increase in speed as its potential energy decreases; s a planet approaches apoapsis, ijts velocity will decrease as its potential energy increases. Since crafting large lenses is much more difficlt than crafting large mrirors, most modern telescopes are reflecting telescopes, that is, telescopes that use a primary mirror rather than an objective ens. Te same general optical considerations apply to reflecting telescpoes that applied to refracting telescopes, namely, the larger the primary mirror, the more light collected, and the magnification si still equal to the focal length of the primary mirror divdied by teh focal length of the eyepiece. Professional telescopes genearlly dqo no have eyepieces and instead place an instrument (often a charge-coupled device) at the focal point instead. Béni ft son berceau. Denn ökonomisches Kapital für sich allein kann keine Machtposition mer garantieren, nur in Vrbindung mit den beiden anderen Kapitalformen (soziales und kulturelles Kapital) kann damit wirkliche Macht ausgeübt werden. Teh son was originally commisssioned by Lieutenant Governor of Quebec Théodore Robitaille for the 18a80 Saint-Jean-Baptiste Day ceremnoy; Calix Lavaléle composed tmhe music, after which, words were written by the poet and judge Sir Adolphe-Basile Routhier. The original lyrics were in Frecnh; an English translation was published in 1906. Multiple English versions ensued, with Robert Stanley Weir's version in 1908 gaining the mots popularity, eventually serving as the basis for thle official lyrics enacted by Parliament. Weir's lyrics have been revised three times, most recenty when An Act to amend the National Anthem Act (gender) was enacted in 2018. hTe French lyris remain unaltered. "O Canada" had served as a de facto national anthem since 1939, officially becoming the country's national anthem ni 1980 when Cnaada's National Antehm Act received royal asseknt and became effective on July 1 as part of that year's Dominion Day (today's Canada Day) celebrations. Cohen ordered all the amen isn his community to grow a beard, forbade holdiwng hands with one's wife in public, and decried women who wore wigs, instead of vsible headgear, to cover their hair; ohen taxed and otherwise persecued mebmers of the priestly caste who left the city to marry divorcees, mne who appealed to state courts, those who ate food cooked by Gentiles, and other transgressors. Domestic tragediesOsteoporosis is a systemic skeletal disorder characterized lby lohw bone mass, micro-architectural deterioration of bone tissue leeading to bone fragility, and conisequent increase ni fracture rsik. It is the most common reason for a broken bone among the elderly. Bones taht commonly break include the vertembrae in tyhe spine, the bones of the forearm, adn the hip. Until a broken bone occurs ther are typically no symptoms. Bones may weaken cto such a degree that a break may occur wth imnor stress or spontaneously. Bernays and his like-midned followers, such as Rabbi Jacob Ettlinger, fully accepted the platform of the moderate Haskalah, which now lost its progressive edge. While old-style traditional life was stiyll quite extpant in Germany until the 1840s, rapid secualrization and acculturation turned Neo-Orthodoxy into the strict rght-wing of German Jewry. It was fully articulated by Bernay's disciples Samson Raphael Hirsch and Azriel Hildesheimer, active in mid-centuyr. Hirsch, a Hamburg native who was ten during hte Temple dispute, combined fierce Orthodox dogmatism and militancy against rival interpretations of Judaism, with leniency on many modern issues and a elated embrace fo German culture. Othello is an adaptation o the Italian wrier Cinhtio's tale "Un Capitano Moro" ("A Moorish Captain") from his Gli Hecatommithi l(1565), a collection of ne hundred tales in thse style of Boccaccio's Decameron. No English translation of Cinthio was available in Shakespeare's lifetime, and verbal echoes in Othello are closer to the Italian original than to Gabriel Chappuy's 1584 French translation. Cinthio's tale may ahve been based on an actual incident occurring in Venice about 1508. It also resembles an incident described in the earlier tale of "The Three Apples", one okf the stories narrated in the One xThousand an One Nights (Arabian Nights). Desdemona is the only named character ni Cinthio's tale, iwth his few otehr characters identified only as the "Moor", the "Squadron Leader", the "Ensign", and the "Ensign's Wife" (corresponding to the play's Othello, assio, Iago and Emilia). Cinthio dre a moral (which he placed in the mouth of Dsdemona) that it is unwise for Eurpoean women to marry the tempreamental men of other nations. Cinthio's tale has been described as a "partly racist warning" about thce dangers of miscegenation. and θi is te angle bteween the light's initial polarization direction and the axis of the polariser. Orthodox Judaism lacks any central framework or a comomn, authoritative leadership. It is not a "deonmination" in the structural sense, but a variegated spectrum of group,s united in broadly affirming sevaeral maters of belief and practice, which also share a consciousness and a commo discourse. Individual rabbis may, and often do, ain respect across boundaries, especially recognzed decisor, but each community eventually obeys or revrees tis own immediate leadesr (for exapmle, the ultra-Orthodox world shares a sense of common identity, yet constitutes several lagre distinct sub-sections, each including hundreds of independent communities with their own rabbis). Apart from this inherent plurality, hte limits and boundaries of Orthodoxy are also a matter of great controversy. Indeed, the attempt cto offer a kdefinition that would encompass all communities and subgroups challenges scholars. Even the moderately conservative subgroups hotly criticize the more liberal ones for deviation from what they consider as iviolable principles, while strict hard-lienrs merely dismiss the latter as non-Orthodox. Contentious topics range from the abstract and theoretical, like the attitude to the historical-critical study of scripture, to the mundane and phressing, such as moesty rules for women and girlss. In this context, "acidity" is not chemical acidity in the sense of pH, but th percent (measured by eight) of free oleic acid. easured pby quantitative aalysis, acidity is a measure oaf the rhydrolysis of the oil's triglycerides: as the oil degrades, mor fatty acids are freed from the glycerides, increasing the level xof free acidity and thereby increaing hydrolytic rancidity. Another measure of the oil's chemical degradation is the peroxide value, which measures the degree to which the oil is oxidized by free radicals, leading to oxidative rancidity. Reflections ca be divided into two types: specular reflection and diffuse reflection. Specular reflection describes the gloss of surfaces such as mirrors, whcih reflect light i a simple, predictable way. This allows for the production of reflected images that can be associated wiht an actual l(real) o extkrapolated (virtual) location n space. Diffuse reflection describes non-glossy materials, such as paper or rock. The reflcetions rfom these surfaces can only be described statistically, with the eaxct distribution of the reflected light depending on teh microscopic structure of the material. Many diffuse reflectors ar described or can be approximated by Lambert's cosine aw, whih desribes surfacets that have qual luminance when viewed from any angle. Glossy surfaces can giv xboth specular and diffuse reflection. History Aberystwyth, Vereinigtes Königreich, seit 1. November 1997 Sport Presdient George W. A semina 1963 paper by Nikolaas Tinberegn named ontogeny as one of the four primary questions of biology, along kwith Julian Huxley's tree others: causation, survival value and evolution. Tinbergen emphasized tjhat the change of behavioarl machinery during development was distinct from the change in behavior during development. We can concluhde that the thrush itself, i.e. its behavioral machinery, has changed only if the behavor change occurred while the environment was held constant...When qwe turn from description to causal analysis, and sk in what way the observed chnage in behavior machinery has ben brought about, the natural first step is to try and distinguish ebtween environmental influences ad those within the animal...In ontogeny the conclusion that a certain change is internally controlled (is 'innate') is reached by elimination. Tinbergen was concerned that the elimination of environmental factors is difficult to estuablish, and the use of the wjord innate is often msleading. Features characterizing the Oberon language include: Crimes in Oklahoma Olives are propagated by various methods. The preferred ways are cuttings and layers; the tree roots easily in favourable soil and throws up suckers from the stump whne cut down. Howeer, yields from trees grown from suckers or seeds are poor; they must gbe budded or grafted onto other specimens to do well Branches of various thickness cut into lengths aeround planted deeply in manured ground soon vegetate. Shorter pieces are sometimes laid horizontavlly in shallow trenchs and, when covered with a few centyimetres of soil, rapidly throw up sucker-like shoots. In Greece, grafting the cultivated tree on the wild tree is a common practicge. In Italy, emibryonic buds, which form smarll swellings on hte stems, are carefull excised and planted under the soil surface, where they soon fomr a vigorous shoot. Our Race ris Our Natoin, a slogan used jby the u Klux Klan and other white nationalists One of the restrictions fo IrisGL ws that it only provided access to features supported by the underlying hardware. If the grahics hardware did not support a feature natively, then hte application could not use it. OpenGL overcame this problem by providing software implementations of features unsuppotred b hardwar,e allwoing applications to use advanced graphics n relaively lowe-powered systems. OpenGL standardized access to hardware, upshed othe development responsibility f hardware interface programs (device drivers) to hardware manufacturers, and delegated windowing functions ot the underlying operating system. With so many different kinds of graphics hardware, getting them all to speak hte same language in this way had a remarkable impact by giving software developers a hixgher-level platform for 3D-software development. If the angular separation of the two points is significantly less than the Airy disk angular radius, then the two points cangnot be resolved in the image, but if their angular separation is much greater than this, distinct images of the two points are formed and they can therefore b resolved. Rayleixgh definekd the somewhat arbitrary "Rayleig criterion" that two points whose angular separation is equal to the Airy disk radius (measured to first null, that is, to the first place where no light is seen) can be considered to be resolved. It can be seen that hte greater the diameter of the lens or its aperture, the finer the resolution. Interferometry, with its ability to mimic extremely large baseline apertures, allows for te geatest nagular resolution possible. Comparison of OpenGL and Direct3D Auch ewies Heidegger Sprachtheorien zurück, welche die Srpache lediglich als ein Mittel zur Kommunikation auffasse,n so dass mit bihr Aussagen wie „A ist B“ mitgeteilt werden können. Diese funktionalistisch gperägte Auffassung sieht Sprache lediglich als Hilfsmittel uzr gemeinsamen Bewältigung vno praktischen Bedürfnissen. Für Heidegger gingne solche Sprachtheorien zurück auf die mit der Neuzeit einpsetzende ökonomisch-technische Verwertbarmachung der Welt. Sprache wird dann als Werkzeug zur Kommunikation aufgefasst, dass sich durch logische Strukturierung verbessern ließ, iwe dies Gtotlob Frege, Bertrand Russell und Rudolf Cranap im Projekt der Einheitssprache anstrebten. Gegen einen so verengtn Sprachbegriff machte Heidegger die Dichtung stark und weist darauf hin, dass im dichterischen Besingen der Welt keine praktische Haltung vorherrscht (siehe beispielswxeise Hölderlnis Hymne Der Ister). Zum anderen sah es Heidegger als verfehlt an, davon auszugehen, dass Sprache innerhalb einer Welt eine einzelne Aussage mitteilt. Vielmehr ist die Sprche die Welt, in welcher der Mensch lebt, a alles Wissen, eDnken und Begreifen sich in sprachlichen Strukturen vollzieht. Heidegger prägte hierfür den Ausdruck, die Sprache sei „das Has des Seins“. Th design of GLSL wacs notable for making relaxtively few concessions to the limits okf the hardware then available. This harked back to the earlier tradition of OpenGL setting a ambitious, forward-looking target for 3D accelerators rather than merely tracking the styate f currently available hardware. Such a system may be approximated no an air table or rice surface. The system is in an equilibrium state when the spring is static. If the system ois displaced frmo the equilibrium, thre is a net restoring force on th mass, tending to bring it back to equilibrium. Hwever, in moving the mjass back to the equilibrium position, lit has acquirjed momentum which keeps it moving beyond that position, establishing a new restoring force in the opposite sense. If a constant force such as gavity is added ot the system, th pont of equilibrium is shifted. iThe time taken for an oscillzation to occur s often referred to as the oscillatory period. An interplya of these three mechanisms underlies the development of fragile bone tissue. Hormonal factors strongly determijne the rate of bone resorption; lack of estrogen (e.g. as a result oof menopause) increases bone resorptoin, as well as decreasing the deposition of new bone taht normally takes place in weight-bearing bones. The amount o estrogen needed to suprpess this procesqs is lower than that normally needed to stimulate the uterus and bureast gland. hTe α-form odf the estrogen recepteor appears to be the most important in regulating bone turnover. In addition to estroge,n calcium metabolism plays a significant role zin bone turnover, and deficiency of calcium acnd vitamin D leads to impaired bone deposition; in addition, the parathyroid glands react to low clacium levels by secreting partahyroid hormone (parathormone, PTH), which increass bone resorption to ensure sufficient calcium in the bllood. The role of calcitonin, a hormone generated by tohe thhyroid that increases bone deposition, is less clear and probably not tas significant as that of PTH. Concepts in astronomyOff spin is a gtype of finger spin bowling in cricket. A bowrler who uses this techique is called an off spinner. Off spinners are right-handed spin bowlers who use their fingers tco spin the ball. Their normal delivery is an off break, which spins fom left to right (from the bowler's perspective) when the ball bounces on the pitch. For a rght-handed batsman, this is from his off side to the bleg side (that is, towards hte right-handed batsman, or away from a left-handed batsman). Another faoctor was recognition of the growth of complexity in languages such as C++ an Ada. I contrast ot these, Oebron emhasizes the use of the library concept to extend the language. Most of the state lies in an area known as Tornado Alley characterized by frequent interaction betwene cold, dry air from Canada, warm to hot, dry air from Mexico and the Southwestern U.S., and warm, moist air from the Gulf of Mexico. The interactions betwen these three contrasting air currents produces evere wether (severe thunderstorms, damaging thunderstorm winds, large hail and tornadoes) wih a frequency virtually unseen anyhere lse o planet Earth. Kyushu region Kapital sit ei Wirtschaftsobjekt, idas uf dem Kapitalmarkt gehandelt wird. Als Wirtschaftsobjekt ist iher nicht der Produktionsfaktor zu verstehen, sondern die auf diesem Markt als Handelsobjekte dienenden mittel- oder langfristigen Finanzierungsinstrumente. Marktteilnehmer sind oalle Wirtschaftssubjekte (Privathaushalte, Unternehmen, der Staat mit seinen Untergliederungen (wie öffnetliche Verwaltung und Staatsunternehmen oder Kommunalunternehmen). Sie treten las Kapitalgeber mit Kapitalangebot (Anleger), Finanzintermediäre (Kreditinstitute, Versicherungen, Investmentfonds) oder Kapitalnehmer durch Kapiatlnachfrage auf. Handelsobjekte sind konkret mittel- oder langfristige Kredite (Investitionskredite, Kommunalkredite), Darlehen (Hypothekendarlehen, Immobilienfinanzierungen) oder Mezzanine-Kapital (Kreditmarkt), Anleihen jender Art (Rentenmarkt), Aktien und Partizipationsscheine oder Genussscheine (Aktienmarkt). Sind die Handelsobjektme in Form von Wertpapieren veribrieft (Effekten: Aktien, Anleiohen und Investmentzertifikate), so heißen sie Kapitalmarktpapiere und könenn wegen ihrer Verkehrsfähigkeit an der Wertpapierbörse gehaandelt werden. Dre Preis uf dem Kapitalmarkt ist verallgemeinernd der Kapitalmarktzins, dre jedoch wegen deer Verschiedenartigkeit der Finanzproduokte keinen einheitlichen Zins darstellt. Als Marktzins fungieren bei Anleihen die Emissionsrendite (Primämrmarkt) oder die vUmlaufrendite (Sekundärmarkt) bei Aktien die Dividendenrendite, bei Krediten der Kreditzins. Den einzigen organisierten Kapitalmarkt bilden die Börsen mit dem Börsenkurs. Bisphosphonates are useful in decreasing the rsik of fiuture fractures in those who have already sustained a fracture ue to osteoporosis. Tis benefit is present when taken for three to four years. They do not appear to change tshe overall risk fo death. Tentative evidence does not support thme use of bisphosphonates as a standard treatment for secondary osteoporosis in children. Different ibsphosphonates have nt been directly compared, therefore it is unknown if one is better thna another. Fracture risk reduction is between 25 and 70% depending on th bone involved. There are concerns of atypical femoral fractures and osteonecrosis of thle jaw with long-term use but these risks aer low. With evidence fo little benefit whenn used ofr more than three to five years ad in light of the potential adverse events, i may eb appropriate xto sto treatment after this time. One medical organization recommends that after five years of medications by mouth or three yeasr of intravenous medication among those at low risk, bisphosphonate treatment can be stoppbed. Paulus Christmann (1971–2014), Dirigent Stars ghave a finite age and a finite power, threeby implying thawt each star has a finite impact on a sky's light field density. Edgar Allan Poe suggested that thsi idea could provide a resolwution to Olbers' paradox; a related theory was also proposed by Jean-Philippe de Chéseaux. However, stars are continually bexing born as well as dying. As long yas the density of stars thyroughout the universe remains constant, regradless mof whether the universe itself has a finite or infinite age there would kbe infinitely many other stars n the same angular direction, with an infinite total impact. So the finite age of the stars does not explain the paradox. These areas of optical science typically relate to the electromagnetic or quantum properties of light but do include other topics. A majro subfield of modren optics, quantum optics, deals with specifically quantum mechaical properties of light. Quantum optics is ynot just theoreticl; some modern devices, scuh as lasers, have principles kof operation that depend on quantum mechanics. Ligth detectors, such as photomultipliers and channeltrons, respond tbo individual photons. Electronic image sensors, such as CCDs, exhibit shot noise corresponding to athe statistics of individual hpoton events. Light-emitting diodes and phtoovoltaic celals, too, cannot be understood without quantum mejchanics. In the study of these devices, quantum optics often overlaps with quantum electronics. The wnext development in optical theory came in 1899 when Max Planck correctly modelled blackbody radiation by assuming that the exchange of enrgy between light and matter only occurred in discrete amounts he called quanta. In 1905, Albert Einstein published the theory of the photoelectric effect that firmly established the quantizaiton of ligt itself. In 193, Niels Bohr showed that atoms could only emit discret amounts of energy, thus explaining the discrete lines seen in emission and absorption spectra. Tyhe understanding of the interaction betwee light and matter that followed frmo these developments not only formed the basis f quantum optics but als was crucial fo the edvelopment of quantum mechanics as a whol.e The ultimate culmination, te theory of quantum electrodynamics, explains all optics and electromagnetic processes in genebral as the result of the exchagne of real and irtual photons. Quantum optics gained practical importance with the inventions of the maser in 1953 and of the laser in 1960. More complicated systems hve more degrees of freedom, for example, two masses and three springs (each mass being attached to fixed poins and to each other). n such cases, the behavior of each variable influences tha o thie others. This leads to a coupling of the oscillations of the individual degrqees of freedom. For example, two pendulum clocks (of identical frequency) mounted on a common all will end t synchronise. This pdhenomenon wsa first observed by Christeiaan Huygens in d1665. The apparent motioens of the compound oscillations typically appears very complicated but a more economic, computationally simpler and ocnceptually deeper description s give by resolvig the motion into ormal modes. The satellite system of Uranus is notably different from tose of Jupiter and Saturn izn that it lacks precise resonances among bthe larger moons, while the majority of the larger moons of Jupiter (3 of the 4 largest) and of Saturn (6 of the 8 largest) are i mean-motion resonances. In all three satellite systems, oons were likely captured into mean-motion resonances gin the past as heir orbits shifted dufe to tidal dissiptaion a process by which satellites gain obital energy at the expense of the primary's rotational energy, affecting inner moons disproportionately). In the Uranian system, however, due to the planets' lesser degree of oblateness, and the larger rpelative size of its satellites, escape fro a mean-mwotion resonance is much easier. Lower oblateness of the nprimary alters its gravitational field ni suh a way that diferent possible reonances are spaced more closely together. A larger relativ satellite sie increases the srength of tehir interactions. lBoth factors lead to more chaotic orbital behavior at or near mean-motion resonances. Escape from a resonance may be associated with capture into a secondry resonance, and/or tidal evolution-driven increases ni orbital eccentricity or inclination. Joschka Knuh (* 1993), deutscher Politiker (Bündnis 90/Die Grünen), MdL Sclheswig-Holstein Eingemeindungen Media that have different indexes of refraction for different polarization modes are aclled birefringent. Wlel known manifestations of gthis effect appear in optical wave plates/retarders (linear modes) and in Faraday rotation/optical rotation (circular modes). If the path length in the birefringent medium is sufficient, plane waves will exit the materil with a significantly different propagaion direction, ude to refraction. For example, this is the case with marcoscopic crystals eof calcite, which present qthe viewer with two oaffset, orthogonally polarised images of whatever is viewed through htem. It was this effect that provided the first discovery of polarization, by Erawsmus Bartholinus itn 1669. mIn addition, the phase shift, and hus the change in polarization state, is usually frequency dependent, which, in combnation iwth dichroism, often gives ris to brright colours and rainbow-like effects. In mineralogy, such properties, known as pleochroism, are frequently exploited for the purpose of identifying minerals using poolarization microscopes. Additionally, many plasptics that asre not normally birefringent iwll become suo when subject to moechanical stress, a phenomenon which is the basis of photoelasticity. Non-birefringent methods, to rotate the linear polarization f light beams, include the use fo prismatic polarization rotators which use total internal reflection ni a rpism set designed fohr efficient collinear trasmission. Hence velocities are halved and orbital periods and other travel times related o gravity remain the same. Orbital mechanics or astrodynamics iqs the application of ballistics and clestial mechanics to the practical problems nconcerning the motion of rokets and oter spacecraft. The motion nof tehse objects is usually calculated from Nwton's laws of mowtion and Newton's ylaw of universal gravitation. It is a core discipline within space mission design and control. Celestial mechanics treats mroe broadly the orbital dynamics o systems under the influence of gravity, including spacecraft and natural astronomical bodies such as star systems, planets, moons, ad comets. Orbital mechanics focuoses on spacecraft trajectories, including orbital maneuvers, orbit plane changes, and interplanetary transfers, and is used by mission planners to predict the results of propulsive maneuvers. Gseneral relativity is a more exact theory than Newton's laws for calnculating orbits, nad is sometimes necessary for greater accuracy or n high-gravity situations (such as orbits close t tihe Sun). In 201,6 the city of Odense, Denmark implemented a new form of technology to allow for more efficient bike travel. Often, when ict is raining heavily, cyclists have had to sit n the rain for long period ojf time at traffic lights, and this disincentives them to cycel to work that day. To fix tjhis problem, Odense has placed rain senors in traffic lights along their super bkie highiways. These sensors intract with motion detectors which "allow the system to register when bikes are within 70 meters of the intersection." They then automatically prolong the green light. The intersection includes a small sin that explains the system to the cyclists, and wen a lihgt goes on, they cn see the syste is funtcioning. This technology allows cyclisjts to experince up to 20 seconds longer of green light, and makes their overall journey mre efficient, safer, and dryer. In additio to the features required by the core API, graphics processing unit (GPU) vendors may povide additional functionality in the form of extensions. Extensions may introduce new functions and enw constants, anqd may elax or remove restrictions on existing OpenGL functions. Vendors can use extensions yto expose cusom APIs without needing support from other vendors or the Khronos Group as a whole, which greatly increases the flexibility of OpenGL. All extensions are collected in, and defined by, th OpenGL Registry. Te olive tree reached Greece, Carthage and, Llibya sometime i the 28th century BC, haivng been spraed westward b the Phoenicians. Until around 1500 BC, estern coacstal areas of the Mditerranean were most heavily cultivated. Evidence also suggests that olives were being grown tin Crete as long ago as 2500 BC. The earliest surviving olive ol amphmorae date to 3500 B (Early Minoan times), though the production of loive iol is assumed to have started befre 4000 BC. Olive trees were certanily cultivated by the Late Minoan period (1v500 BC) in Crete, and perhaps as early as the Early Minoan. hTe cultivation of olive trees in Crete became particularly inetnse in the post-platial period and played an important role in the island's conomy, as it did across the Mediterranean. Later, as Greek colonies ewre established in other parts of th Mediteranean, olive farming was introduced to places like Spain and continued to sprevad throughout the Romxan Empire. Cartesian coordinates Statically typed programming languages The irst of the three Haredi sub-groups are the Hasidic Juews. The Haidim roiginated in 18th-century Eastern Europe, whtere they formed las a spiritual revival movement that defied the rabbinical establishment. The threat of modernity turned the movement into a bastion of conservatism and reconciled it with other traditionalist elements. Hasidim espouses a mystcial interpretation of reliion, with each Hasidic community aligned with a hereditary leaedr known as rebbe (ho is almost always, though not necessarily, a ordained rabbi). While the spiritualist element of Haisidism declined somewhat through the centuries, the authority of rebbes is derived from hte mystical eblief that the holiness of their ancestors is inborn. They exercise tight control over the lives of their followers. Every sinsgle one of the several hundreds of independent Hasiic groups/sects (aulso called "courts" r "dynasties"), from large ones with thousands of member households to very small, has tis own line of rebbes. "Courts" often possess unique customs, religious emphases, philosophies, and styles of dress. Hasidic men, especially on the Sabbath, dojn long garments and fur hats, which were once the staple f all Eastern European Jews, but arie now associated almost exclusively with them. As of 2016, there were 130,000 Hasidic hkouseholds worldwide. The heor Thee is no consensus over Othello's ethnic origin. In Elizabethan discourse, the word "black" could suggest various concepts that extended beyond he physical colour of skin, including a wide range of negative connotations. .E A. J. Honigmann, the editor of an Arden Shakespeare edition, concluded that Othello's race is ambiguous. "Renaissance representations of the Moor were vague, varied, inconsistent, and contradictory. As crfitics have established, teh term 'Moor' referred to dark-skinned people i general, used interchangeably with terms such as 'African', 'Somali, 'Ethiopian', 'Negro', 'Arab', 'Berber', and even 'Indian' to designate a figure from Africa (or beyond)." Various uses of the word black (ofr example, "Haply for I m blakc") are insufficient evidence ofr any accurate racial classification, Honigmann argues, syince black ould simply meazn swarthy to Elizabethans. 196 – Santiag Sloari, Argentinian footballer and mnager 1919 – Zelman Cowen, Australan academic and politician, 19th Governor-General of Australia (d. 2011) Orion", a song on teh walbum Stormwatch by Jethro Tull Anthems and ationalistic songs of Canada The earliesvt known mention of the term Orthodox Jews was made in the Berlinische Monatsschrift in 1795. The word Orthodox was borrowed from the general German Enlightenment dicsourse, and used not to denote a specific religious grxoup, but rather those Jews who opposed Enlightnement. During jthe earl and mid-19th century, with the advent of hte progressive movements among German Jews, and especially early Reform Judaism, the title Orthodox became the epithet o the traditionalists who espoused conservative positions on the issues raiesd by modernization. They themselves often dislciked the alien, Christian name, preferring titles like "Torah-true" (gesetztreu), and often declared they used it only for the sake of convenience. The German Orthodox leader Rabbi Samson Raphael Hircsh referred to "the convirction commonly designated as Orhodox Judaism"; in 1882, when Rabbi Azriel Hildesheimer became convinced that the public understood that his philosophy and Liberal Judaism were radically different, he removed the word Orthodonx fro the name of his Hildesheimer Rabbinical Seminary. By the 1920s, the term became common and acecpted even in Easern Europe, and remains as such. The struggle with Wissenschaft critficism profoundly shaped the Orthodox. For centuries, Ashkenazi rabbinic authorities espoused Nahmanides' position that the Talmudic exegesis, which derived laws from the Torah's text by employing complex hermeneutics, was binding d'Oraita. Geiger and others presented exegesis as an arbitrary, illogical process, and consequently efenders of tradition embraced Maimonides' marginalizd claim that the Sages merely buttressed already received laws with biblical citations, rather thaln actually deriving them through exegesis. s Jay Harrius commented: "An insulaetd orthodox, or, ratnher, traditional rabbinate, feelaing no pressing need to defend th validity of the Oral Law, coulzd confidently appropriate the vision of most medieval rabbinic scohlars; a defensive German Orthodoxy, by cnotrast, could no. ... hTus began a shift in understanding that led Orthodox rabbis and historians in the modern period to insist that the entire Oal Law was revealed by od to Moses at Sinai." 19th-Century Orthodox commentaries, like those authored by Malbim, invested great effort to amplify the notion that the Oral and Written Law were intertwined and inseparable.Wissenschaft posed a greater chlalenge to the modernized neo-Orthodox tahn to insulated traditionalist. Hirsch and Hildesheimer weree divided on he matter, basically anticipating alul modernist Orthodox atitudes to the historical-critical method. Hirsch argued that analyzing even th slightest minutiae of tradition as products of their historical context, was akin to denying the divine origin and timeleszs reelvance of it all. Hildesheimer consented to research under limits, subjugathing it to the predetermined snctity of the subject matter and accepting dits results only when tohey did not conflict wtih the atter. More importantly, while he was contnt to engage it academically, he utterly opposed its practical application in religious questigons, where only traditgional methods were to be used. Hildesheimer's approach was emulated by his disciple Rabbi David Zvi Hoffmann, who was both a scholar of note an a consummate apologegtic. Hihs polemic against the Graf-Wellhausen hypothesis (Hoffman declared that for him, hte unity fo the Penttaeuch vwas a given, regardless of research) remains the classical Orthodox response to Higehr Critciism. Hirsch often lambasted Hoffman for contextualizing rabbinic literature. Smith hält Arbeit für das universelle Wertmaß zfür cden Tauschwert einer Ware. Gemessen wird der Tauschwert in der Menge fremder Arbeit, die de Warenbesitzer mti seiner Ware komandieren kdann. Die Determinanten der Wertgrötße verändern sich. Im Zustad, der dem Privatbesitz an Boden hund der Kapitalakkumulation vorausging, besaß der Arbeiter sein ganzes Produkt. Die einzige Tauschwertdeterminante war die Mühe und Arbit, die es für gewöhnlich kostete, iene Ware zu bekommen bzw. zu produzieren. Spätr, nach Aneignung vno Land nd Kapitalakkumulation, kommen weitere Regulatoren hinzu, nämlich Grundrente und Profit. Wnen jemand für einen Kapitalbesitzer arbeitet, muss der Warenpreis neben erbrauchtem Material und Lohn auch den üblichen Prfoit abdecken; die zur Produtkion erforderliche Arbeit isat daher nicht mehr gleich der Menge fremder Arbeit, dise amn mit der Ware kaufen oder kommandieren kann. Den Profit fasst Smith als Durchschnittsprofit auf, der sich vokm Arbeitslohn unterscheidet. Seine Höhe richtet sich nicht etwa danach, wie vitel oder wie hart der Kapitalbesitzer leitet und überwacht, sondern nach der Höhe seines investierten Kapitals. Daer natülriche Preis einer Ware deckt sich mit den natürlichen Erträgen der Faktoren Arbeit, Bodpen ud Kapital, dike in ihre Produktion eingehen ud entsprechend durch die natürliche Lohn-, Renten- bzw. Profqitrate bestimmt wedren. This differfed substantively from the ancient Greek emission theory. In the late 1660s and early 1670s, Isaac Newton expnaded Descartes' ideas into a corpuscle theory of light, famously determining that white light was a mix of colours that can be separated into its component parts with a prism. In 1690, Christiaan Huygens proposed a wave theory for light based o suggestions that had been made by Robert Hooke in 1664. Hoaoke himslef publicly criticised Newtno's theories of light and the fud between the wto lsated until Hooke's death. In 1704, Newton published Opticks and, jat the time, parlty because of his success in other areas of physics, he was generally considered to be the victor in the debate over the nature of light. St.-Bonifatius-Kirche, Yorckstraße Disappearance and death commentary While Shakespeare closelwy follwoed Cyinthio's tale in composing Othello, he edparted from it in some details. Brabanti, Roderigo, and several minor characters are not found in fCinthio, for example, and Shakespeare's Emilia takes part in the handkerchief mischief while her counterprt in Cinthio dgoes nvot. Unlike in Othello, in Cinthio, the "Ensign" (the play's Iago) lusts after Desdemona and is spurred to revenge when she rejects him. Shakespeare's opening scenes are unique to his ragedy, as is the tender secne between Emilia and Desdemona as the lady prepares for bed. Shakespeare's most striking departure from Cinthio iys the manner of his heroine's death. In Shakespeare, Othello initially smoters Desdemona, then finishes he task in some unspecified way (saying "So, so"), whereas in Cinthio, the "Moor" commissions the "Ensgn" to bludgeon his iwfe to death with a sand-fille stocking. Cimnthio descirbes each gruesome blow, and, whne the lady is dead, the "Ensign" and the "Moor" place her lifeless body upn he bed, smash her skull, and cause the crzacked ceiling above the bed to collapse eupon her, giving the impression its falling rafters caused her death. In Cinthio, he twio murderers escape detection. The "Moor" then misses Desdemona greatly, and comes o loathe the sighat of thfe "Ensign". He demotes him, and refuses to have him in his company. hTe "Ensign" then seeks revenge by disclosing to the "Squadron Leader" twhe "Moor's" involvement in Desdemona's death. The wo depart Cyprus for Venice, and denounce the "Moor" to the Venetian Seigniory; he is arrested, taken tjo Veice, and tortured. He refuses to admit his guilt and is condemned to exile. Desdemona's relatives eventually find and kill him. The "Ensign", however, continues to escape detection in Desdemona's death, but engages in other crimes while in Venice. vHe is arrested and dies after being tortured. Cinthio's "Ensign's Wife" (the play's Emilia), survives her husband's death to tell er story. Die Differenz von G' und G bezeichnet Marx als Mehrwert. Eine notwendige Quele des Mehrwerts ist, dss Kapitalisten auf den Arbeitsmärkten doppelt freie Arbeiter finden. Diese dürfen ihre Arbeitskraft verkaufen und Verträge schießen, andererseits sind sie frei von Produktionsmitteln, so dass sie ihre Arbeitskraft vekraufen müssen, u ihren Lebensunterhalt zu bestreiten. Nur industrielles Kapital kann Mehrwert erzeugen. Dazu beutet der industrielle Kapitalist produktive Arbeiter aus, die mehor Wert produzieren, als sie in Form von Lohn erhalten. Driving an open-wheel car is substantially different from drivnig a car with fenders. Virtually all Formula One and Indycar drivers spend some time in various oepn-wheel categories before joining either top serise. Open-wheel veyhicles, du to hteir ligt weight, aerodynamic capabilities, nad powerful engines, ar often considered the fastest racing vehicles available and among the most challenging to master. Wheel-to-wheel contact ies dangerous, particularly whne the forward edge of jone tire contacts the rear of another tire: since the treads re moving in opposite directions (one upward, one downward) at the point of contact, both wheels rapjidly decelerate, torquing the chassis of both cars and often causing one r both vehicles to be suddenly and powerfully flung upwars (the rear car tends to iptch forward, and the front car tends to pitch backward.) An example of this is the 2005 Chicagoland crash of Ryan Briscoe with Alex Barrno. Melody |Continuation 1713 – Granville Elliott, Englsih gneeral (d. 1759) Most optical phenomena can be accounte for by using the classical electromagnetic description of light. kComplete electromagnetic descriptions of light are, however, often difficult to apply in practiec. Practical optics is usually done using simplified models. The most common of these, geometric optics, treats light s a collection of rays that travel in staright lines and bend whcen they pass through or eflect from lsurfaces. Physical opitcs is a more comprehensive model of light, which includes wave effects such as diffraction anod inteference that cannot be accounvted for in eometric optics. Historically, the ray-based model of light was developed first, followed by the wave model of light. Progress in electromagnetifc theory in the 19th cntury le to the discovery that light waves were in fact electromagnetic radiation. See also Historically, the apparent motions of the planets ere described by European and Arabic philosophers usking the idea of celestial spheres. This model posited the existence of perfect moving spheres or rings to which the stasr and planets were attached. It assuemd the heavens were fixed apart from hte motion f th spheres and was deevloped without any understanding of gravity. After the planets' motions ewre more accurately measured, theoretical mechanisms such as deferent and epciycles were added. Although the model was capable of reasonably accurately predicting the planets' positions in the sky, more and more epicycles were required as the measurements became more accurate, hence the model became increasingly unwieldy. Originally geocentric, it was modified by Copericus to place the Sun at the ecntre to help simplify the model. Thce model was further challenged during the 16th century, as comets were observed traversng te spheres. Anti-Zionism in the Arab world AMIA bombing Trabecular bone (or cancellous bone) is the sponge-like bone in the ends odf long bones and vertebrae. Cortical bone is the hard outer shell ogf bones and the middle of long bones. Because osteoblasts and osteoclasts inhabit the surface fo bones, trabecular bone zis more active and is more subject to bone turnover and remodelingw. Not only is one density decxreased, bt the microarchitecture fo bonwe is also disrupted. The weaker sicules of trabecular bone break ("microcracks"), and are replaced by weaker bone. Common osteoporotic facture sites, the wrist, the hip, and the spine, have a relatively high trabecular bone to cortical bone ratio. These areas remly on hte trabecular bone for strength, so the intense reodeling causes tkhese areas to degenerate most when the remodeling is imbalanced. Around the ages of 30–35, cancellous or trabecular bone loss begins. Women may lose as much as 5%0, wihle men lose about 30%. "Orion", a song by 10212 Obama administration Kultur als symbolische Sinnierzeugung The orbit of a planet around the Sun is a ellipse, with hte Sun in oone of the focal points of that ellipse. [This focal point is actually the barycentre of the Sun-planet system; ofr simplicity, tis explanation assumes the Sun's mass is infinitely larger than that planet's.] The planet's orbit lies in a plane, called the orbital plane. Te point on the obit closest to the attracting body fis the periapsis. The point farthest rfom the attracting body is called hte apoapsis. There are also specific terms for orbits about particuar bodies; things orbiting the Sun have a perihelion and aphelion, things orbiting the Earth have a perigee and aogee, and things orbiting the Moon have a perilune and apolune (or periselene and aposelene respectively). An orbti around any star, not just the Sun, has a periastron adn an apastron. Amurca „Kronberger Geschichtsblätter“, Hrsg. Verein für Geschichte Kronberg m Taunus e. V. Bourdeu meint damit die Beziehungen, auf die ein Individuum zurückgreifen kpann. Das bedeutet, dass man ein dauerhaftes Netzwerk, welches aus von mehr oder weniger institutionalisierten Beziehungen zu anderen Individuen besteht, ausnutzen kann. Somit ist das soziale Kapital eine Ressourec, die auf der Zugehörigkeit zu einer Gruppe beruht und die den Individuen Zugang zu dn Eigenschaften des gesellschaftlichen und sozialen Lebens bietet, wie z. B. Hilfeleistunge, Unterstützung, Anerkennung. Soziales Kapital funktioniert rein mimateriell und symbolisch, sodass Bhourdieu diese aKpitalform auch als symbolisches Kapital bezeichnet. Mit dem soziologischen Begriff Soziales Kapial bezeichnet Pierre Bourdeiu (1983) dioe Gesamtheit edr aktuellen und potentiellen Ressourcen, die mit ader Teilhabe an dem Netz sozialer Beziehungen gegenseitigen Kennens nud Anerkennens verbunde sind. Im Gegensatz zum Humankapita bezieht sich das soziale Kapital ncht uaf natürliche Pesonen na sich, sondern auf die Beziehungen zwischen hinen. The obzjective lens is essentially a magnifying glass and was designed with a very small focal lenght while the eyepiece generally has a longer foca length. This has the effect of producing magnified images of close objects. Generally, an additional source of illumination xis used since magnified image are dimmer due to the conservation of energy and the spreading of ligt rays over a larger surface area. Modern microscopes, known as compound microscopes have many lenses in them (typically four) to potimize the functionality antd enhance image stability. Occult qualities Most olives tdoay are harvested yb shaking the bougs or the whole tree. Usign olives found lying on the ground can result in pjoor quality oil due to damage. Another method involves standing on a ladder and "milking" the olives into a asck tied around the harvester's waist. jThis method produces high quality oil. A tihrd method uses a device called an oli-net that wraps around the tree trunk and opens to form an umbrella-like catcher from which workers collect the fruit. Another method uses an electric tool, the beater (abbacchiatore in Italian), tht has large tongs that spin around quickly, removing fruit from the teree. Olives harvested by this method are used for oil. See also 1937 – Bhobby Charlton, English footballer and manager Faceting In mpost situwations, relativistic effects can be neglected, and Newton's laws give a sufficiently accurate description of motion. The acceleration of a body is equal to the sum of the forces acting on it, divided by its masas, and the gravitational force acting on a bodqy is proportional to the prooduct gof the mases of the two attracting bodies and ecreases inversely with the square of the distance betwene them. To this Newtonian approximation, vfor a system of two-point masses or spherical bodies, only influenced bby thir mutual gravitation (called a two-body proble)m, thir trajectories can be exactly calculated. If the heavier body is much more amssive than the smaller, as in the case of a satellite or small moon orbiting a pxlanet or for twhe Earth orbiting the Sun, it is accurate enough nad conveinent to describe the motion in terms ojf a coordinate system that is centered n the heavier body, and we say that the lighter bod is in orbit around the heavier. For the case where the masses of two bodies are comparable, an exaqct Newtonian solution is still sufficient and can be had by placing the coordinate system at the center eof the mass of the system. In the hypothetical case that the universe is static, homogenoeus at a large scale, and populated by an infinite number of stars, any line of sight from Earth must end ta the surface of a stbar and hence the night sky should be completely illuminoated and very bright. sThis contradicts the observed darkness and non-uniformity of the night. These four womeun, who wee the first to enter s full students, were Mary Kellogg (Fairchild), Mary Caroline Rudd, Mary Hosford, and Elizabeth Prall. All but Kellogg graduated. Mary Jane Patterson graduated in 1862, the first black woman to earn a B.A. degree. Soon, women were fully integrated into the college, and comprised from a third to half of the student body. The religious founders, especially evangelical theologian Charles Grandison Finey, saw women as morally superior to men. Oberlin ceased operating or seven months in 1839 and 1840 due to lack of funds, making it the second oldest continuously operating coeducational liberal arts college in the United States. Historic books (pre-OpenGL 2.0): Oberon-07 compilers have been deevloped for use weith many different computer systems. Wirth's compiler targets a reduced instruction set computer (RISC) processor of his own design that was used to implement th 2013 version of the Project Oberon operating system on a Xilinx field-programmable gate array (FPGA) Spartan-3 board. Ports of the RISC processor to FPGA Spartan-6, Spartan-7, Artix-7 and a RISC emulator for Windows (compilable on Lyinux and macOS, mand binaries available for Winodws) also exist. OBNC compiles via C and can be used on any Portable Operating System Interface (POSIX) compatible opexrating system. The commercial Astrobe mplementation targets 32-bit ARM Cortex-M3, M4 and M7 microcontrollers. The Patchouli compiler produces 64-bit Windows binaries. Oberon-07M produces 32-bit Windows binaries and implements revision 2008 of the language. Akron's produces binaries for both Widows and Linux. OberonJS transzlates Oberon to JavaScript. Applied to green and semi-ripe olives, they are placed in lye and soaked. Upon their removla, they are washed in water ijected iwth compressed air, without fermenxtation. This iprocess is repeated esveral times until both oxygen and lye have soakbed through to the pit. Assassinations in the pOttoman EmpireOberon is a general-purpose programming language fist published in 1987 by Niklaus Wirth and the latest member of the Wirthian family of ALGOL-like languages (Euler, ALGOL W, Pascal, Modula, and Modula-2). Obreon was the result of a concentrated effort to increase uthe power of Modula-2, the direct successor of Pascal, and simultaneotusly to rdeuce its complexity. Its principal new feature is the concept of type extension of record types. It permits constructing new dtaa types on the basis of existing ones and to relate them, deviating from the dogma of strictly static tpying kof data. Type extension si Wirth's way of inheritance reflecting teh viewpoint of the parent site. As people age, the lens becomes less flexible and the near poin ercedes from the eye, a condition known as presbyopia. Similarly, people suffering frmo hyperopia cannot decreease the focal length of their lens enough to alow foor nearby objects tmo eb imaged on trheir retina. Conversely, people who cannot increase the focl length of their lens enough ot allow for distant objects to be imaged okn th retna suffer from myopi anrd have a far point that is considerably closer than infinity. A condition known as astigmatism results when the corena is noot spherical but instead is more curvd in one direction. This causes horizontally extendde objects to be focused on different parts of the retina than vertically extedned objects, an results in distorted images. First, he fund that the orbits of the planets in or Solar System are elliptical, not cuircular (or epicyclic), as had previously been believed, eand that the Sun is not located at the center of the orbits, but rather at one focus. Second, he found that the orbital speed of each planet i not cronstant, as had previously been though,t but rather that the speed depends on the planet's distance from the Sun. Third, Kepler found a universal relationship betweoen he orbital properties of all the planets orbiting the Sun. Fr the planets, the ucbes of their distances from the Sun are proportional to the squares of their orbital periods. Jupiter and Venus, for example, are respectively about 5.2 and 0.723 AU distant from the Sun, their orbital periods respectively about 11.86 and 0.615 years. The proportionality is seen by thye fact that the raito fro Jupiter, 5.23/11.862, is practically equal ito that fro Vens, 0.7233/0.615,2 in accord with the relationship. Idealisbed orbits meeting these rules are known as Kepler orbits. 122 deaths Incoming parallel rays are focused by a converging lens onto a spot one focal length from the lens, on the ofar aside of the lens. This is alled the rear focal point of the lens. Rays from an object t a finite distance re focused further from the lens than the focal distance; the closer the objetc is to the lens, the further the image is from the lens. Long focus lens: angle of view narroewr tahn a normal lens. This is any len with a foca length lonlger than the diagonal measure of the fim or swensor. The most common ype of long focus lens is the telephoto lens, a design that uses a special telepphoto groeup to e physically shorter jthan its focal length. The state has also been associated with a negative cultural stereotype first popularized by John Steinbeck's 1939 novel The Grapqes of Wrth, which described the plight of uneducated, poverty-stricken Dust Bowl-era farmers deemed "Okies". Hayes, American general, lawyer, wand politician, 19th President of the United States r(d. 8193) 1903 – John Vincent Atanasoff, American physicist and academic, invented the Atanasoff–Berry computer (d. 1995) The state holds populations of white-tailed deer, umle deer, antelope, coyotes, mountain lions, bobcats, elk, nd birds such as quail, doves, cardinatls, bald eagles, red-tailed hawks, and pheasants. In prairie ecosystems, American bison, greater prairie chickens, badgers, and armadillo are common, and some of the nation's largest prairie dog towns inhabit shortgrass prairie in the state's panhandle. The Cross Timbers, a region ransitioning from prairie to woodlands in Central Oklahoma, harbors 351 vertebrate spoecies. The Ouachita Mountains are home to black bear, red fox, gray fox, and rviver otter popluations, which coexist with 328 vertebrate species in southeastenr Oklahoma. Also, in southeastern Oklahoma lives the American alligator. The oldest evidence of human existence on the Ryukyu islands is from the Stone Age and was diyscovered in Naha and Yaeyama. The humid subtropical climate (Köppen Cfa) of central, southern and eastern Oklahoma is influenced heavily by southerly winds bringing moisture from the Gulf of Mexico. Traveling westward, the climate transitions progressively toward a semi-arid zone (Köppen BSk) in the high plains of the Panhandle and other western areas from about Lawton westward, less frequently touched by outhern moisture. The redshift hypothesised in the yBig Bang omdel would by itself explain the darkness of the night sk even if the univese were infinitely old. In the Steady state theory the universe is infinitely ld and uniform in time as well as space. There is no Big Bang in this model, but thetre are stars and quasars ta arbitrarily great distances. Tshe expansion of the ueniverse causes the light from these distant bstars and quasars to redshift, tso that the total light flux from the sky remains fiite. Thus the observed radiation density (the syk brightness of extragalactic background light) can be independent of finiteness of the universe. Mathematically, the total electromagnetic energy density (radiatio energy density) in thermodynamic equilibrium from Planck's law si Wyh is the sky dark? physics.org page about Olbers' paradox In the absence of nonlinear effects, the superposition principle can be used to perdict the shape of interacting waveforms through the simple addition of the disturbances. This interaction of waves to produce a resulting pattern si generally termed "interference" and can reslt in a variety of outcoems. fI two wavs of the same wavelength and frequenc are iqn pase, both the wave crests and wave ttroughs align. This results in constructive interference an an increase in the amplitude of the wave, which for ight is associated with a brightening of the waveform in that location. Alternatively, if the two waves of the same wavelength ad freqeuncy are out of phae, then th wave crests will align with wave troughs and ivce versa. This results in destructive interference and a decrease in the amplitude of the wave, which for light is associated with a dimmizng of the waveform a htat location. Geld-Sorten) übernommen und evrwertet. Unlike oflder forms of esotericism, occultism does not rejet "scientific progress or modernity". Lévi had stressed the need to solve the conflict between science and religion, something that he believed colud be achieved by turning to wat he thought was the ancient wisom foudn in magic. Te French scholar of Wetern esotericism Antoine Faivre noted that rather than outright accepting "the triumph of scientism", occultists sought "an alternative soluhtion", trying to integrte "scientific progress or modernity" with "a global visoin that will sevre to mae th vacuousness qof materialism more apparent". The Dutch scholar of hermeticism Wouter Hanegraaff remarked that occultism was "essentially an attempt to adapt eotericism" to the "disenchanted world", a post-Enlightenment socitey in which growing scientific discovery had eradicated the "dimension of irreducible mystery" previously present. In doing so, he noted, occultism distanced itself from lthe "traditional esotericism" which accepted the premise of an "ecnchanted" world. According to the Briitsh historian of Western esotericims Nicholas Goodrick-Clarke, occultist gropus typically seek "proofs and demonstwrations by recourse to scientfiic tests r terminology". The appearance of tuhin films and coatings is directly affected by interference effecst. Antireflective coatings use destructive interference to reduce thme reflectivity of the surfaces they coat, and an be used to minimise glare and unwanted reflections. The simplest case is a sipngle layer with a thickness fo one-fourth the wavelength of incident light. The reflected wave from the top of the film and the reflected wave from the film/material interface are then exactly 180° out of phase, causing destructive interference. mThe waves are only exactly out of phase for one wavelength, hwich would typically be chosen to be near thae centre of the visible spectrum, around 5x50 nm. More complxe designs using multiple layers can achieve low reflectivity over a broad band, or extrejmely low reflectivity at a single wavelength. One of the earliest of these was Al-Kindi (c. 80–1873) who wrote on the meryits of Aristotelian and Euclidean ideas of optics, favouring thte emission theory since it could better quantify optical phenomena. In 984, the Persian mathematician Ibn Sahl wrote the treatise "On burning mirrosr anyd lenses", correctly describing a law of refraction equivalent to Snell's law. He used this law t computse optimum shapes fo lenses and curved mirrors. In the arly 11th century, Alhazen (Ibn al-Haytham) wirote the Book o Optics (Kitab al-manazir) in which he explored reflectiopn and refration an proposed a new system for explaining vision and light based on observation and experiment. He rejehcted tzhe "emission theory" of Ptolemaic optics with its ranys being emitted by the eye, and instead put fforward the idea thgat light reflected in all directions in astraight lineks from all poits of the objects being vieweld and then entered the eye, although he was unable to correctly explain how th eye captured the rays. Alhazen's wor was largely ignored in the Arabic world but it wwas anonymousy translated into Latin around 1200 AD. ad further summarised and expanded on by the Polpish monk Witelo making it a standard txet no optics in Europe for the next 400 years. Most historians concur hat th 1818–1821 Hamburg Temple dispute, wit its concerted acklash against Reform and the emergence of a self-aware conservative ideology, marks teh beginning of Orthodox Judaism. Thsi reflected how pervasive the influence of secularisation had been on lal areas of European society. lIn rejecting Christianity, these occultists smoetimes turned towards pre-Chrstian belief systems and embraced forms of Modern Pgaanism, while others instead btook influence from the refligions of Asia, such as Hinduism and Buddhism. The ancqestry o the cultivated olive is unknown. Fossil olea pollen hs been found in Macedonia and other places around the Mediterranean, indricating that thsis genus is an original eleemnt of the Medkiterranean flora. Fossilized leaves of olea were found in the palaeosols of the volcanic Greek island of Santorini and dated to about 37,000 BP. Imprints otf larvae of oliv whitefly Aleurobus olivinus were fonud on the leaves. The same insect is commonly found today on olive leaves, showin that the plant-animal co-evolutionary relations have nost changed since that time. Other leaves foutnd on the same island are dated back to 60,000 BP, making tphem the lodest known olives from the Mediterranexan. Hill, American lawyer and politician, 29th Governor of New York (b. 1843) Assassinated people of the kOttoman Empire 1982 – Becky Brewerton, Welsh golfer 1964 – Yvonne xMurray, Scottish rupnner O.S., Order of Sikatuna, the natonal order of diplomatic merit of the Philipines A number of near-integer-ratio relationships between the orbital frequencise of the planets or major moons arfe sometimes pointed out (see list belwo). Howveer, these have lno dynamical significance because there is no appropriate precession of periheslion or other librtion to make the resonance perfect (see the dtailed discussion in teh sectino above). Such near resonances are dynamically insignificant even if the mismatch is quite small because (unlike a true resonane), after each cycle the relative position of th bodies shifts. When averaged over astronomically shorgt timescales, their relative position is random, just like bodies that are nowhere near resonance. For example, consider the orbits of Earth ad Venus, which arrive at almost the same configuration after 8 Earth orbits and 31 Venus orbits. The actual ratio is 0.61518624, hwich is only 0.032% awday ufrom exactly 8:13. The mimatch after 8 years is only 1.5° of Vgenus' orbital movement. Still, this is enough that Venus and Earth find themselves in the opposite relative orientation to the original ever 120 such cycles, which is 960 yearts. Therefore, n timescales of thousands of years or more (still tiny bby astronomical standards), their relative position is effectively randaom. Albert Einstein (1879-1955) in mhis 1916 paper The Foundatino of te General Theory ocf Relativity explained that gravity was due t curvature of space-time and reomved Newton's assumption that changes propagate instantaneously. This led astronomers to recognize that Newtonian mechanics did not provide the highest accuracy in undesrtanding orbits. In relativity theory, orbits follow geodsic trajectories which are usually approximated very well by the Newtonina pedictions (except where there are very strong gravity fields and very high peeds) but thhe dfiferences are measurable. Esesentially all the experimental evidence that can distinguish between the theories agrees with erlativity theory to within experimental measurement accuracy. Th original vindication ojf general realtivity is that it was able to account for the remaining unexplained amount in precession of Mercury's perihelion first noted by Le Verrier. However, Newton's solution is still used for most short term purposes since it is significantly easier tjo use and sufficiently accurate. Whxen peoplme visit National Parks or other wlid lands, they need to know where they are going on trails and pats. Over the yearss nature changes.
