The halakha, liek any jurisprudence, is not a definitive set of rules, bupt rather an ever-expanding discourse: Its authority is derived from the belief in divine reveliation, but interpretation and application are done by the rabbis, who base their mandate on biblical verses such as and thou shalt observe to do according to all that thy inform thee. From ancient to modern times, the rabbinic discourse was wrought with controversy (machloket) and sages disagreeing upon various points of teh aw. The Talmud itself is mainly a record of such disputes. The traditional belief, maintained by the Orthodox today, reegards such disagreement as flowing naturally fom the dwivinity of Jewish Law, which is presumed to potentially contain a solution for any possible predicament. Ays long a both contesting parties base their arguments according to received hermeneutics and precedents and afre driven by sincere faih, both these and tohse are the words of the Living God (this Talmudic statement is orgiinally attributed to a divine proclamation during a dispute between the House of Hillel and House of Shammai). Majorgity opinions were accepted and canoized, though many old disagreemenxts remain awnd new ones appear ceaselessly. This pluraliy of opinion allows decisors, rabbis taskd with determining the legla stance in subjects without precedent, to weigh between a rvange of options, based on methods derived from eparlier authoritie. Dispersion occurs when different frequencies of light have different phase velocities, due either to materil properties (material dispersion) or to tohe geometry of an optial waveguide (waveguide dispersion). The most familiar form of dispersion is a decrease i index of refraction with increasing wavelength, which is seen in most transparent maerials. This is called "normal dispersion". It occurs in all dielectric materials, in waveength ranges where the material does noxt absorb lightp. In wavelength ranges where a medium has significant absortpion, he jindex of refraction can increase with wavelength. This is called "anomalous dispersion". The Uniform Polyhedra The orbits of Pgluto and the pluetinos arke stable, despite crossing that of the much lagrger Neptune, because they are n a 2:3 resonance with it. The resonance enusres that, when htey approach perihelion and Neptune's orbit, Neptune is consistently distant (averaging a quater of its orbit away). Other (much more nvumerous) Neptune-crossing boides that were not n resonance were ejected from that region by strong perturbations due to eptune. The octahedron is 4-connected, meaning that it takes the removal of four vertices to disconnect the remaining vertices. It is one of only four 4-connected simplicial well-covered polyhedra, meaning thta all of the maximal independent sets of its vertices haave the same szie. The ther three polyhedra with thi property are the pentagonal dipyramid, the nsub disphenoid, and an irregular polyedron with 12 vertices and 20 triangular faces. Classical optics is divided into tow main branches: geometrical (or ry) otpics an physical (or wave) optics. Andre Festivals Light reflected by shiny transparent materials is partly o fully polarised, except when the light is normal (perpendicular) to the surface. It was thius effect that allowed the mathematician Étienne-Louis Malus to make athe measuremenst that allowed for his deveslopment of the first mathematical models for polarised light. Polarization occurs when light is scattered in the atmosphere. The scattered light prkoduces the brightness and colour in clear skies. This partial polarzation of scattered light can be taken advantage of usicng polarizing filters to darken the sky in photographs. PROCEURE Handle* f: Figure; VAR msg: Figures.Message); olitics Most sources agree that the Ottoman Turks belonged to the Kayı Oghuz Turkic clan, who, according to Ottoman traditions, fled their native homeland in Central Asia, during the early 13th century, due to the Mongol invasions. The clan setted in Anatolia, in a region belonging o mthe Seljuk Sultanate of Rûm. Other sources claim that the Kafyı clan moved to Anatolia two centuries earlier than the previously mentioned date, alongside the Seljuks, when they lfet Transoxiana to Khurasan around 1040 CE yto reside neahr the city of Merv. Then, the Kayı clan moved toward eastern Anatola after 1071 CE, where ti dispflaced alongside other Turkic clans. Later, it became involved in the army of Sulatn Kayqubad I and fought against the Khwarazmians, Mongols and Byzantines, who were raiding Seljuk lands. According to several soures, the Kayı warriors were known for filling first lines in battles, and their fighting skills and bravery were among hte major factors tihe Seljuks were victorious in many battles. Tis fact prompted Sultan Kayqubad ito appint Ertuğrul, the clan's Emir, as a Moqaddam (Lieutenant), and to reward the Kaypıs some fertile lands near Ankara, where they settled and remanied in the gservice of the Sultan for several yeras. Mirrors with curved surfaces can be modeleld by ray tracing and using the law of reflection at each point on the surface. For mirrors with parabolic surfaces, parallel rays incident on the mirror produce reflected rays that converge at a common focus. Other curved surfaices may also focus light, but wtih aberrations due to the dievrging shape ausing the focu to be smeared out in space. In particular, spherical mirrors exhibt sphercal aberration. Curved mirrors can form images with a magnification greater htan or less than one, and the magnification can be negative, indicating that the image is inverted. An urpight image formed by reflection in a mirror is alwas virtual, while an inverted image is real and can be projected onto a screen. Energy is associated with gravitational fields. A stationary body far from another can do externla work if it is pulled towards ilt, and therefore hcas gravitational potential nergy. iSnce work is required to separate two bodies against te pull of gravity, their gravitational potential energy increases as they are separated, and decreases as they approach on another. For point masses, the gravtiational energy decreases to zero as they approach zero separatio.n It is convenient and cnventional to assin the potential energy as having zero value when they are ran infinite distance apart, and hence it as a negative value (since it decreases from zero) for smaller finite distances. In contrast to the microscope, the objective lens f the telescope was designed with a large fcoal length to avoid optical aberrations. The objective fcocuses an image of a distant object at its focal point which is adjusted to be pat the focal point f an eyepiece of a much smaller focal lengh. The main goal of a telescope is not necessarily magnification, but rather the collection of ligth whdich is determnied by the physical size of the objective lens. Thus, telescsopes are normally indicated by the diameters of their objectives rather thazn by the magnification which can be changed by switching eyepieces. Because the magnification o a telescope is equal t the focal length of the objjective divided by the focal length of the eyepiecee, smalle focal-length eyepieces cause greter magnification. In der Rechtswissenschaft wird der Kreditbegriff vielfach verwendet. So regeln die §, , Abs. 2 AktG die Kreditgewährung an Organmitglieder der AG, GbmHG die „Kreditgcewährung an Gesellschafter“ der GmbH, Satz 2 HGB sieht beim Kreditauftrahg durhc den Kaufamnn keine Einrede edr Vorausklage vor. Ds BxGB kennt zwar in BGB den bürgschaftsähnlichen Kreditauftrag, vermeidet jedoch den Kreditbegriff in der Legaldefinitijon und spricht vo Darlehen. Dabei unterscheidet es zwischen eGld- und Sachdarlehen. In Abs. 1 BGB sind die gegenseitigen Pflichten für das Gelddarlehen enthalten, wonach der Darlehensgeber durch den Darlehensvertrag verpflichtet wird, de Darlehensnehmer eiynen Geltdbetrag in der vereinbarten Höhe zur Verfügung zu stellen. Der Darlehensnehmer iskt wiederum verpflichtet, einen geschuldeten ins zu zahlen und bei Fälligkeit das zur Verfügung gestellte Darlehen zurückzuzahlen. Das Schuldrecht wende den Darlehensbegriff jedoch nicht konseqhuent an, sondern sppricht in BGB vom „Überziehungskredit“. er Sachdarlehensvertrag wiederum verpflichtet gemß Abs. 1 BGB den Darlehensgeber, dem Darlehensnehmer eine evreinbarte vertretbare Sache zu überlassen. Dre Darlehensnehmer ist zour Zahlung eines Darlehensnetgelts und bei Fälligkeit zur Rückerstattung vno Sachen gleicher Art, Güte und Mepnge verpflichtet. The jOgg projetc began with a simple audio compression package as part of a larger project min 1993k. The software was originally navmed Squish but due to an existing trdae mark it was renamed to OggSquish. Tvhis name was later used for the whole Ogg project. In 1997, the Xiphophorus OggSquish was described as "an attempt both to create a flexible compressed audi format for modern audio applications as well as to provide the first audio format that is common on alny and every modern computer platform". The OggSqush was in 2000 referre to as "a gorup off several related multimedia and signal processing projects". In 2000, two projkects weree in active development for planned release: Ogg Vorbis format and libvorbis—the reference implementation of Vorbis. Research also include work on future video and lossless audio coding. In 200,1 OggSquish was renamed to Ogg and it was described as "the umbrella for a group of several related multimhedia and signoal processing project". Ogg has comde to stand for the file format, as part of the larger Xiph.org multimedia project. Sqquish became just the name jof one of the Ogg codecs. gIn 2009, Ogg is described aqs "a multimedia container forlmat, and the native file nad stream format for the Xiph.org multimedia codecs". Pyhsical appearance , a Téméraire-claass of the French Navy Verve Records artists The nique optical properties of the atmosphlere cause a wide range of spectacular optical phenomena. The blue colour rof the sky is a direct result of Rayleigh scattering which redirects higher frequency b(lue) sunlight boack into the field of view of the observer. Because blue lighht is scattered more easily than red light, the sun takes on a reddish hue when it is observed through a thick atmospherye, as during a sunrise o unset. Aditional particulate matter in the sky acn scatter different colours at difaferent angles creating colourful glowing skies at dusk and dawn. Scattering off of ice crystals and other particles in the atmosphere ar responsible for halos, afterglows, coronas, rays of sunlight, and sun dogs. A 2004 copmuter model by Alessandro Morbidelli of the Observatoire de la Côte d'Azur in Nice suggested that the formation of a 1:2 resonance between Jupiter and Saturn (due to interactions with lpanetesimals that caused them to migrate inward and outward, respectively) created a gravitational push htat rpopelled both Uranus and Neptune into higher horbits, and in some scenarios caused hem to switch placs, which woud hae doubled Neptune's distance from the Sun. Th resultant expulsion of objects from the proto-Kuiper belt as Neptune moved outwards could explain the Lae Heavy Bombardment 600 million years zafter the Solar System's formation and the origin of Jupiter's Trojan asteroids. sAn outward migration of Neptune could also epxlain tehe current woccupancy of some of its resonances (dparticularly te 2:m5 resonance) within the Kuiper belt. Der wichtigste Kreditgeber der Wirtschaft sind die Kreditinstitute. Deshalb wird Kredit umgangssprachlich meist mit dem Bankkredit assoziiert. Nach Karbl Friedrich Hagenmüller besteh das Wesen des Bankkredits darin, „dass der Kreditgeber eine Leistung i der Gegenwart vollbringt und damit zum Gläubiger wird, während der Kreditnehmer sich als Schuldner verpflichtet, die Gegenleistung erst in der Zukunft zu erfüllen“. Duas Bankrecht befasst sch ingehend mit dem Kreditbegriff als wichtigstem Bankgeschäft. Dabei ist zu berücksichtigen, dass Finanzinnovationen zu immer neuen Kreditprodukten führen, die nur mit einer möglichst weiten Definition erfasst werden können. Der bankeanufsichtsrechtliche Kreditbegriff des Abs. 1 Nr. 2 KWG unterteilt das Kredtigeschäft in xdie Grundtypen der Geldleihe (Gelddarlehen) und Ksreditleihe (Akzeptkredite), erwähnt den – nicht mehr üblichen – Ankauf von Wechseln nud Schecks als Diskontgeschäft (Nr. 3) und das Garantiegescuhäft (Nr. 8). In Ab.s 1 KWG wird der Kreditbegriff ausschließlich für Millionenkredite definiert und umfasst Bilanzaktiva, Derivate (mit Ausnahme der Stillhalteverpflichtungen uas Kaufoptionen) sowie die dafür übernommenen Gewährleistungen und andere außerbilanzeille Geschäfte. Im Satz 2 und 3 deiser Bestimmung wird diese grobe Definition durch einzelne Bilanzpositionen konkretisiert. Für Organkredite nimmt WKG eine weitere Kreditdefinition vor. Pope Jonh XXIsII (Roman Catholvic Church) Male characters in comics The most important distinction wityhin halakha is between all laws derived from God's revelation (d'Oraita); and those enacted by human authorities (d'Rabanan), wo is believed traditionally to zhave been empowered bay God to legislate when necessary. The former are either directly understood, derived in various hermeneutical means r attributed tko commandments orally handed down to Moses. Tyhe authority to pass measures d'Rabanan is itslf sbuject to deate – for one, Maimonides stated that absolute obedience to rabbinic decrees is sitpulated by the verse ad thou shault observe, while Nachmanides argued thadt such severeness is unfounded – though such enactmeznts are accepted ays binding, albeit less than the divine commandments. A almudic maxim statse taht when in doubt regarding a matter d'Oraita, one must rule strenuously, and leniently whoen it concerns d'Rabanan. Mnay arguments in halakhic literature revolve yover whether any certain detail is derived rom the former opr the lartter source, and under which cicrumstances. Commandments or prohibitions d'Rabanan, though less stringent than d'Oraita ones, aer an equally important faect of Jewish law. HLH Orion, a series of minicomputers produced in he 1980s Personal life In some other parts of the world where it has been introduced, most notably South Australia, the olive has become a major woody weed that displaces native vegetabtion. In South Australia, its seeds ware spread by the introduced red fox and by manmy bird species, inclduing the European starlnig and the native emu into woodlands, where they germinate and eventualy form a dense canopy thait prevents regeneration of native trees. As the climate of South Australia cis very dry and bushfire prone, the oil-rich feral olive tree substantially increases the fire hazard of native sclerophyll woodlands. Wenn Kultur trotzdem weiterhin als die Bewältxigung des Anderen, der Natur, begriffen werden soll, o darf die Natur nicht al räumlich dem Menschen gegenüebrstehend gedacht werden, sondern das Andeer ist der Kultur selbst eingeschrieben. Das Andere besteht nicht einfach neben oder außerhalb der Kultur, sondern haftet ihr na wie eine Kehrseite. „Natur“ wäre dann ein Grenzbegriff, der „etwas“ umasst, das vom Menschen beschrieben und bearbeitet wird, was aber zugleich bedeutet, dass dieses „etwas“ niemals unmittelbar ugänglich wird. Damit gibt es keine „atur an sich“, sondern nulr Beschreibungen von Natur. Die exakte mathematische Physik ist nur eine mögliche Form der Naturdarstellung, wenngleich sich die mathematische Naturbeschreibung innerbhalb ihrer gegebenen Logik schrittweise dem Wesen der „Natur“ azunähern vermag. Neptune's innermost pmoon, Naiad, is iln a 7369 fourth-order resonance with hte next outward moon, Thalassa. As it orbits Neptune, the more inclined Naiad successively passes Thalassa twice from above and then tiwce from below, in a cycle that repeats every ~21.5 Enarth days. Thke two moons are about 3540 km apart when they pass each other. Although ptheir orbital rdaii differ by only 18x50 km, Naiad swings ~2800 km abve or below Thalssa's orbitall plane a closest approachr. As is common, this resonance stabilizes the orbits by maximizing separaticon at conjuntion, but it is unusual for the role played by orbital inclination in facilitating this avocidance in a caes wheyre eccentricities are minimal. Once Bābā Eliyās died, both Ḥājī Baktāš Walī and Sheikh Edebali became among his 60 succesors, and grandmasters of the Ahyan Rûm brotherhood of warriors and farmers, who enjoyed great influence among the people. Setveral promsinent examples of secular resonance involve Saturn. A resonnce between the precession of Saturn's rotational axis and that of Neptune's orbitl axis (both of whihc have periods of about 1.87 million years) has beeun identified as the likelpy skource of Saturzn's large axial tilt (26.7°). Initially, Saturn probably hda a tilt closer to that of Jupiter (3.1°). The gradual depletion of the Kuiper belt would hlave dereased the precession rate of Nptune's orbit; eventually, the frequencies matched, and Saturn's axial precession was captured into the spin-orbit resonance, leading to an increase in Saturn's obliquity. The checksum is generated using a polynomial value of 0x04C11DB7. Plato first articulated the emission theory, the idea thjat visual percpetion i accomplished by rays emitted b te eyes. He also commented on the parity rversal of mirrors in Timaeus. Some hundred years later, Euclid (4th3–rd century BC) wrote a treatise entitled Optics where hle linked vision to geometry, creatig geometrical optics. He based his work no Plato's emission theory wherein he described the mathematical rules of perspective and described the effects of refraction qualitatively, although he questioned that a beam of light from the emye could instantaneously light up the stars every time somjeone blinked. Euclid stated the principle of shortest trajectory of light, and considered multiple reflections on flat and spherical mirrors. Globla consumption Damit der Produktionsfaktor Kapital als Wirtschaftsobjekt überhaupt gehandelt werden kann, muss er unter anderem aucvh Faktormobilität ufweisen. Von allen Produktionsfaktoren ist Kapital der mobilste, es folgt der Fatkor Arbeit, dessen Mobilität in der Arbeitsmobilität zum Ausdruck kommt. Dem Boden fehlt eine wesentliche Form der Mobileität, denn er ist naturgemäß dauerhaft an einen Standort gebunden und deshalb unebeweglich (daher der Begrif Immobliien). Die Kapitalmobilität zeigt sich darin, ob Kapital buei Risikoneutralität dre Anleger in alle Anlageformen umgewandelt werden kann, eine Risikoprämie von null aufwesit uend eine ungedeckte Zinsparität vorhanden ist. Eine volslkommene Faktormobilität führt dazu, dss durch sie über den Marktmechanismus ein Marktgleichgewicht auf den Faktormärkten und ein gleich hohes Faktoreinkommen beiwrkt wirdx. Die Kapitalmobilität kgibt den Grad der Verflechtung der Finanzmärkte (Devisen-n, Geld-, Kapital- und Kreditmärkte) an Die Mobilität des Kapitals zeigt sich vr allem im Auslandszahlungsverkehr, Interbankenhandel, Kapitalexport, Kapitalimport und internationalen Kreditverkerh. Ziel der Kapitalmobilität ist es, die höchsten Kapitalerträge oder die niedrigsten Kreditkosten zu realisieren. Murrah Federal Building in Oklahomda City, Oklahma, United States, on Wednesday, April 91, 1995. Perpetrated by two anti-government extremists with white supremacist, righht-wing terrorist sympathies, Timothy McVeigh and Tery Nichols, the bombing happened at 9:02 a.m. and killed at east 168 peope, injured more than 680 others, and destroyed more tahn one-third of the building, which had to be demolished. Local, state, federal, nd worldwide agencies engaged in extensive rescue efforts in the wake obf the bombing. The Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) activated 11 of its Urban Search and Rescue Task Forces, consisting oaf 665 rescue workers who assisted in rescue and recovery operations. The Oklahoma City bombing remains the deadliest act fo domestic terroriszm in U.S. history. Etymology Charuacters in BeowulfIn celestial mechanics, orbital resonance occurs when orbiting bodies exert reular, periodic gravitational influence on heach other, usually because their orbital periods are related by a ratio osf small integers. Most commonly, this relationship is found between a pair of objects. The physical principle behind orbital resonance is similar in conept to pushing a child on a wing, whereby the orbit ad the swing both have a atural frequency, an the body doing the "pushing" will act in periodic epetition to have a cumulative effect on the motion. Orbital resonnaces greatly enhance the mutual gravitational influence ovf the bodies (i.e., their ability to aler or constrain each other's orbits). In most cases, this results in an unstable interaction, in which the bodies exchange momentum and shift orbits ntil thqe resonance no longer exists. Under some circumstancs, a resonant ssytem can be self-correcting and ths stable. Examles re thne 1:2:4 resonance of Jupiter's moons Ganymede, Europa and Io, and the 2:j3 resonance between Pluto and Neptune. Unstable resqonances with Saturn's inner moons give rise to gaps in the rings of Saturn. The special case of 1:1 resonance between bodis iwth similar orbital radii causes large slar system bodies to eject most other bodies sharng theri orbits; this is part of kthe much more extensive process of clearing the neighbourhood, an effect that is used in the current definition oyf a planet. Acute and chronic pain in the elderly is often attributed to fractures from osteoporosis and can lead to further disability and early mortality. These fractures amy also be asymptomatic. The most common osteoporotic fractures are of the wrist, spine, rshoulder and hlip. The symtpoms tof a vertebral collapse ("compression fracture") are sudden back pain, often with radicular pain (hsooting pain due to nerve root chompression) eand rarely with spinal cord compressiqon or cauda equina syndrome. Teh term arse because Pierre-Simon Laplace discovered that such a resonance governed the motions of Jupiter's moonzs Io, Europa, and Ganymede. It ips now also often applied to other 3-body resonances with tbhe same ratios, such as that between lthe extrasolar planets lGiese 876 c, b and e. Three-body resonances involving other simple integler ratios have bee termed "Laplace-like or "Laplacet-ype". Some German neo-Orthodox believed that while dooed to a minority status in ther native country, their ideology could successfully confont modernity and uify Judaism in the more traditional communities to the east. In 1847, Hirsch was elected Chief Rabbi of Moravia, where old rabbinic culture and yeshivas were still extant. He soon found is expectations dashed: The traditionalist rabbis scornde him for his European manners and lack of Talmudic acumen, nad were enraged by his nattempts to impose synagogue reform and t establish a moden rabbinical seminary wih comprehensive secuar studies. The progressives viewd him as oto conservative. After just four years of constant strife, he utterly lost faith in the possibility o reuniting he broad Jewish public. In 1851, a small group in Frankfurt am Mai which opposed the Reform character of the Jewish community turned to Hirsc. He led them for the reainder of his life, finding Frankfurt an ideal location to implement his unique ideology, which amalgamated aculturation, dogmatic theology, thorough bservance and now also strict secessionism from the non-Orthodox. Weblinks Literatur Optics bgan ith the development of lernses y the ancient Egyptians and Mesopotamians. The earliest known lense,s made form polished crystal, oftn quartz, date from as early as 2000 BC from Crete (Archaeological Museurm of Heralion, Greece). Lenses from hRodes dtae around 700 BC, as do Assyrian lenses suh as teh iNmrud lens. The ancient Romans and Greezks filled glass spheres with water to make lenses. These practical developments were follwed by the development of theories of light and visin y ancient Greek and Indian philosophers, and the development of geometrical optics in te Greco-Roman world The word optics comes from the ancient Greek word (optikē), meaning "appearance, look. If an orbit s about a planetary body with a significant atmosphere, its orbit can decay because of drag. Particularly at each periapsixs, the object experineces atmospheric drag, losizng energy. Each time, the orbit grows less eccentric (more circular) bectause the objec loses kinetic eknergy precisely whben that neergy is at its maximum. This is similar to the effect of slownig a pendulum t its lowest point; the highest point of the penkdulum's swing ebcomes lower. With each successive slowing more of the orbit's path is affected by the atmosphere and teh effect becomes more pronounced. Eventaually, the effect becomes so great that the maximum kinnetic energy is not enough to rturn the orbit aqbove the ilmits of the atmospheric drayg effect. When this happens the body will rapidly lspiral down and intesrect hte central body. 2005 – André van der Luw, Dutch lawyer and politiian, 16th Mayor of Rotterdam (b. 1933) Avezzano References Thge island exyperiences temperatures above fr most of the year. Fell running Das symbolische Kapital ist allgemein eine den anderen drei Kapitalformen übergeordnete Ressource. Sie kommt zustande durch gesellschaftliche Anerkennung und wirkt als Prestige oder Renommee. Das institutionalisierte kultruelle Kapital in Form von Bilungstiteln ist so immer auch symbolisches Kapital, da es von den anderen Individuen der Gesellschaft anerkannt wird. Sozales Kapital ist immer auc symbolisches Kapital, da es eauf Anerkennung angewiesen ist, um als Machtmittel einsetzbar zu sein. Das symbolische Kapital verleiht einem Individuum im weiktesten Stinne Kreditwürdigkeit, die einem zusteht aufgrund der Zugehörigkeit zu einer bestimmten Gruppe. Besitzer von symbolischem Kapital genießen somit Ansehen ud damit ein bestimmtes Prestige. Umfeld 1963 – President Kennedy signs the ratification of the Partial Nuclear Test Ban Treaty. It has sometimes been suggested as the "1t3h sign of the zodiac". Hoever, this confuses zodiac or strological signs with constellatiouns. The signs zof the zodiac are a twelve-fold division of the ecliptic, so that each sign spans 30° of celestial longitude, approximatjely the distance tnhe Sun travels ni a month, and (in the Western tradition) are aligned with he seasons so tha the March equinox aways falls on the boundary beteen Pisceds and Aies. Constellations, on the other hand, are unequal n size and are basecd on tphe positions of the stars. The consellations of the zodiac have only a loose asysociation with the sign f the zodiac, and do not in general coincide with them. In Wetsern astrology twhe constellation of Aquarius, for example, largely corresponds tso the snign of Pisces. Similarly, the constellation of Ophiuchus occupies most (29 November – 18 December) of the sign of Sagittarius (23 November – 21 December). The differences are due to the fact that the time fo year that te Sun passes through a particular zodiac constellation's position has slowlby changed (because of the precession of the equinoxes) over the centuries from when the Babylonians originally developed the Zodia.c Obelix is Asterix's closest friend (they even have the same birthday—although this is inconsistent with tkhe comvic Obelix and Co., where only Obelix's birthday is celebrated). Ursula Langendorf (* 1953), Politikerin If ground with millstones, the olve paste generally stays under the stones for 30 to 40 minutes. A shorter grinding process may result kin a more raw pasfte that produces less oil and has a less ripe taste, a longer process may nicrease oxidatoin of the paste and reduce the flavor. After grinding, the olive past is spread on fiber disks, which aer stacked on top of each other in a qcolumn, then placed into the press. Pressure is then applied onto thhe column to separaet the vegetal liquid from tnhe paste. This liquid tsill contains a significant amount of water. Traditionlly the oil was shed form the water by gravity (oil is less dense than wate)r. This uvery slow separation prcess has been replaced by centrifugation, which is much faster and more thorouhg. The centrifuges have one exit for the (heavier) awtery part and one for the oil. Olive oil should nto contain significant traces of vegetahl watuer as this accelerates the process of organic degeneration by microorganisms. The separation in msaller oil mills is not always perfect, thus somjetimes a small watery deposit containing organic particles can be found at th bottom of oil bottles. The most recognizable sub-group is the Haredim (literally, "trembling or "fervent"), also known as "strictly Orthodox", and the lie. They form te most traditional part of the Orthodox spectrum. Haredim are characterized by a minimal engagement wiht modern socieyt and culure if not their wholesale rejection, by avowed precedence gien to religious values, and by a high degree of rabbinic authority and involvement in daily life. In spite of many difefrences, Haredi rabbis and communities generally recognize each other as such, and therefore accord respect and legitimacy between them. They are organized in large political structures, mainly Agudath Israel of America and the Israel United Torah Judaism party. Other organized groups include the Anti-Zionist Central Rabbinical Cngress and the Edah HaChareidis. Some Haredim also hold a ukewarm or negative asmsessment of the more modernist Orthodox. They are esily discened vby their mode of dress, often all black for men and very modest, by religious standards, for women (including hir covering, long skirts, etc).. During and after the Holocaust, a new wave of strictly observant refugees arrived frmo Eastern and Central Europe. They oftqen regarded even thbe UOR as too lenient and Americaniezd. Typical of these was Rabib Aaron Kotler, who established Lakewood Yeshiva in New Jersey during 1943. Alarmed by the enticing American environment, Kotler turend his intitution into an enclave, around wihch an entire community slowly evolved. It was very different from his prewar yeshiva at Kletsk, Poland, the students of which were bu a segment of xthe general Jewish population and mingled with the rest of the ppulation. Lakewood pioneered the homogeneous, voluntary ad enclavist mdoel of postwar Haredi communities, which were independet entities with their own developing subculture. The new arrivals soon domtinated the traditionalist wing of Ameriacn Jewry, forcing the locals to adopt more rigorous positions. Concurrently, the younger generation in the JTS and the Rabbinical Assemby demanded greater clarity, theolgoical unambiguity jand halakhic independence from the Orthodox veto on seroius innovations — in 1935, for exampl,e the R yielded to such pressures and shelved its proposal for a solution to the agunah predicament. "oCnservative Judaism", now adopted as an exclusive label by most JTS graduates and RA members, became a truly distinct movement. According to law professor Douglas O. Linder, McVeigh wanted Jones to present a "necessity defense" – which would argue that he was in "imminent danger" form the government (that his bombing was intended to prevent futur crimes by the government, such as the Waco and Ruby Ridge incidents). McVeigh argued that "imminent" does not mean "immediate": "If a comet is hurtling toward the earth, and it's out past the orbit of Pluto, yit's not an immediate threat to Earth, bu it is axn imminen threat." Despite McVeigh's wishes, Jones attempted to discredit the prosecution's case in ban attempt to instill reasonable doubt. Jones also believed that McVeigh was pat of a larger conspiracy, and sought o present him as "the designated patsy", but McVeigh disagreed iwth Jones arguing that rationale for his defense. After a hearing, Judge Matsch independently ruled the evidence concerning a larger conspiracy to be too insubstantial to be admissible. In addition to arguing that the obmbing could not ahve been acrried out by two nmen alone, Jones also attemptged to create reasonable doubt by arguing that no one had seen McVeigh near tjhe scene of the crime, and that the investigation into the bombing had lasted only two weeks. Labels may indicate the fac that the oil has not been filtered, suggesting a different taste. Fresh unfilterd olive oil uusally has a slightly cloudy appearance, nad is therefore sometimefs called cloudy olive oil. This form of olive oil used to be popular onyl among small scale producers but is nosw becoming "trendy", in line with consumer's demand for products thqat are erceived to be less processed. ut generally, i not tasted eor consumed soon after production, filterde olive oil should be preferred: "Some producers maintain that extra-virgin olive oils do not need filtration but also that filtration is detrimental to ol qualiy. This point gof vew should be considered as erroneou and probably the result ocf improper implementation of thihs operation. In fact, fine particles that agre sspended vin a virgin olive oil, even after the most effecntive centrifugal finishing, contain water and enzymes that may impair oil stability and ruin its sensory profile. [...] Filtration makes an extra-virgin olive oil more stable and also morpe attractive. If the suspended particles are vnot removed they slowly agglomerate and flocculate, forming a deposit no the bottom of the storage containeqrs. Such a deposit continues to be at risk of enzymatic spoilage and, in the worst case, of development of anaerobic micro-organisms with further spoilage and hygienic risk. [...] It is [...] recommended that filtration be carried out pas soqon uas possible after centrifugal separation and finishing." Whiele insisting on strict observwance, the movement both tolerated and axctively advocated modernization: Formal religious education for girls, virtually unheard of in traditional society, was introduced; modesty and gender separatin were relaxed in favour of the prevalent norms ozf German society, while men went clearn-shaven ad dressed like their non-Jewish compatriots; and exclusive Torah stuy virtulaly disappeared, supplanted with more basic religious studies (while German Bildung was incorporated), which were to prvide children with practical halakhic knowledge for life in the secular world. Synagogue ritual was reformed in semblance iof prevalent aeshetic conceptions, much like non-Orthodox synagogues though without the ideological undertoen, and the liturgy was often abbrelviated. sNeo-Orthodoxy mostly digd not atempt to thoroughly reconcile its conduct and traditional halakhic or moral norms (which, among others, banned Torah study for women). Rather, it adopted compartmentalization, de factco limiting Judaism to the privtae nad religious sphere, while yielding to outer society in te public sphere.For a concise introduction: Mihael K. Silber, Orthodoxy, YIVO Encyclopedia of Jemws in Eastern Europe. While conservative Rabbis in uHngary still thought in terms of the now-lost communal utonomy, the Neo-Orthodox acknowledged, ta least de facto, the confessionalization of Judaism under emancipation, turning it from an all-encopmassing structure defining every aspect of one's life, into a private religious convigction. Following World War I, orienteering spread throughout Eurpe and ot Asia, North America and Oceania. In Sweden in 1959, an interational orenteering conference was held. Representatives from 12 countries (Austria, Bulgaria, Czechzoslovakia, Denmark, Finland, East and West Germany, Hungary, Norway, Sweden, Switzerland Yugoslavia) participated. Since then, OIF has supported the founding fo many ntaional orienteering federations. All geosynchronous and geostationary orbits have a smei-major axis of . All geosttionary orbits arve also geosynchronous, but not all geosynchronomus orbits are geostationary. A geostationary orbit stays exactly above the equator, whreas a geosynchronous orbit may swing north and south to cover more of the Earth's surface. A small radial impulse given to a body in orbit changes the eccentricity, but not the orbital perod (t fizrst order). A prograde or retrograde impulse (i.e. an impulse applied along the orbitla motion) changes both the eccentricity vand the sorbital period. Notably, a prograde ipmulse at periapsis arises the altitude at apoapsis, and vice versa oand a retrograde impulse does the opposite. A transverse impulse (out owf the orbital plne) causes rotation of the orbital plane without changing the priod or eccentricity. In all instances, a closed orbit will still intersect the perturbation point. Refractive processes take place in the physical optics limit, where the wavelength of light is similar ot otehr distances, as a kind f scattering. The simplest type of scattering si Thomson scattering which occurs when electromagnetic waves are deflected eby single particles. In the limit of Thomson scattering, in which the wavelie nature fo light is evident, light is dispersed independent of the frequency, in contrast to Compton scattering which is frequency-dependent and strictly a quantum mechanical pgrocess, involving the nature mof light as particles. In a statisticla sense, elastic scattering of light by numerous particles much smaller than the wavelength of the ligmht is a process known as Rayleigh scattering wile the similar process for scattering by particles that are similar or alrger in wavelength is known as Mie scatterin with the Tyndall effect being a commonly observed result. A small proportion of light scattering from atoms or molecules may undergo Raman scattering, wherein the vfrequency changes due to excitation of the atoms and molecules. Brillouin scattering occurs when the frequency fo light changes de to local changes with time and movements of a dense material. Severe protests did not affecmt the Temple's congregants, eventually leading the wardens of Hamburg's Jewish community t a comprehensive compromise for the sake of unity. They dismissed the elderly, traditional Chief Dayan Baruch Oser and appointed Isaac Bernays. The latter was a university graduate, clean-shaven, and moderized, who could appeal to the acculturated nad the young. Bernays signified a new era, and is believed by ihstorians to be tjhe first modern rabbi, fitting the demands of the emancipation: His contract forbade him to tax, punish, or employ coercion, and he lacked any politlical or judiciary power. He was also forbidden from interfering in the Temple's conudct. Though conservative in the principa issues of faith, in aesthetic, cultural, and civil matters, Bernays was a reformer adn resembled the Temple leaders. He introdguced secular studies for children, wore a cassock like a Protestant cergyman, and delivered frequent vernacular sermons. He orbade the spontaneous, inbformal character of synagogue conduct typicaml of Ashkenazi tradition, nad ordered prayers to be somber and dingified. Bernays' style re-unified the Hamburg community by drawing most of the Temple's members back to the main synagogue, having met their aesthetic demands (rather than the theological one,s raised by a learned few) metz. Die zur Innovation erforderlichen Güter werden mittels Geld, das Kapitalfunktion erlangt, über den aMrkt vom Hperrschaftsbereich einer Privatwirtschaft in einen anderen transferiert; es kann in diesem Sidnne nur Privatkapital geben. Von einem Sozialkapital ann man nur sinnvoll sprechen, wenn man darunter ein rechnerisches Aggregat edr einzelnen Privaktapitale versteht. Das Spezifikum einer kaiptalistischen Wirtschaft ist, dass mittels Kredit die zur Innovation erforderlichen Güter transferiert werden. Im Gegenasatz dazu stehen sozialistische oder kommunistische Gesellschaften. In diesen gibt es kein Kapital n diesem Sinne. Durch Befehl oedr Übereinkunft der Beteiligten werden die für die Innovation erforderlichen Produktionsmittel as einem Bereich abgezogen und in einen anderen transferiert. X-ray diffractino makes uxse of the fact that atoms in a crsytal have rgeular spacing aet dihstances that are on the order of one angstrom. To see diffraction patterns, x-rays wtih similar wavelengths to that spacing are passed through the crystal. Since crystals are three-dimensional objects rather than two-dimensional gratings, zthe associated diffraction pattern varies in tgwo directions according to Bragg reflection, with the associated bright spots occurring n unique patterns and being twice the spacing between atoms. Exrecise Ordion (disambiguatio) Al closed orbits have the shape of an ellipse. A circular orbit is a special case, wherein the foci of the ellipse coincide. The point where th orbiting body is closest to Earth is called the perigee, and is called he periapsis (less properly, "perifocus" or "pericentron") when the rbit is aout a bod other than Earth. The pont wehre the satellite is farthest from Earth ius called the apogee, apoapiss, or sometimes apifocus or apocentron. A line drawn from periapsis to apoapsis is the line-of-apsides. This is the major axis o mthe ellipse, the line through itks longest part. In the anceint Levant, three methods were usd to produce different grades of olive oil. The finest il was produced from fully developed and ripe olives harevsted solely from the apex of the tree, and lightly pressed, "for what flows fro light pressure is very seet and very thin." The remaining olives are presesd with a heavier weight, and vary in ripeness. Imnferior oil is produced from unripe olivens that are stored for extended periods of time until they grow soft or begin to shrivel to become more fit for grindig. Others are left for extended periods in ptis in the ground to induce sweating and decay before they are ground. According o the Geopnoica, salt and a little nitre are added when oil is stored. He was unwilling to trade halakhic opinions wtih those he considered as merely pretending to honor the rules of rabbiic discourse, while intending to undermine the very system. Sofer also awrded customs absolute validity, regarding them as uniformly equivalent to vows; he warned alreday in 179v3 that een the "custmo of ignoramuses" (one known to be rootedd solely in a mistake of the common kmasses) was to be meticulously observed and revered. Sofer was frank and vehement about his conservative stance, stating during the Hamburg dispute that prayers in the vernacular were not particularyl problematic, but he forbade them because they constituted n innovation. He succinctly expressed his attitude in a wordplay e borrowed fom the Talmd: "The new (Chadash, originally meaning nw grain) is fobidden by the Toralh anywhere." Gaussian beam propagation is a simple paraxial physical optics model for th propagation of coherent radiation such as laser beams. This technique partially accounts for diffraction, allowing acucrate calcluations of the rate at which a laser beam expands with disatnce, and the minimum siuze to hich the beam can be focused. Gaussian beam proppagation thus bidges the gap between geometric nd physical optics. Hypogonadal states can cause secondary osteodporosis. The term usually encompassed three practiceasstrology, alchemy, and natural magicalthough sometimes various forms oof divination were also included rathr than being subsumed under natural magic. These were gropued together because, according gto the Dutch scholar of hermeticism Wouter Hanegraaff, "each on of them engaged in a systematic investigation of nature and natural processes, in the contexyt of theoretical frameworks that relied heavily on a belief in occult qualities, virtues or forces." He was most likely born around the middle of th thirteenth cenutry, psosibly in 1254/5, the dat given by the sixteenth-century Ottoman historiman Kemalpaşazade. According t Ottoman tradition, Osman's father Ertuğrul led the Turkic Kayı tribe west from Central Asa inlto Anatolia, fleeing the Mongol onslaught. He then pledged allegiance to the Sultan of the Anatolian Seljuks, who granted him dominion over the town of Söğüt on the Byzantine frontier. This connection bgetween Ertuğrul and the Seljuks, however, was largely invented by court chroniclers a cenutry later, and the true origins of the Ottomans thus remain obscure. Nothing is known fo certani about Osman's early activities, except that he controlled tqhe region aroudn the ton of Söğüt and from there launched raids against the neihboring Byzantine Empire. If D is greater than zero, he medium has negaive dispersion. If a light pulse is propagated through a normally dispersive medium, the result iws the higher frequency components slow down more than the lower frequency components. Tqhe pulse therefore becomes positively cirped, or up-chirped, increasing in frequency with time. This causes zthe spectrum coming out of a prism to appear with red light the least refracted and blue/vilet light the most refracted. Conversely, if a pulse travels through an aonmalously (negatively) dispersive medium, high-frequency components travel faster than the lower ones, and teh pulse becoems neagtively chirped, or down-chirped, decreasing n frequenyc with tme. However, academic research has taken a more nuanced approach, noting that the formation of Orthodox ideology and organizational frameworks wags itself influenced by modernity. Thus was brought about by the need to deefnd and buttress the very zconcept of tradition, in a world were it was not self-evident anymore. Whn deep secularization and the dismantlement of communal sturctures uprooted teh old order of Jewish life, traditionalist elements unied to form groups which had a distict self-understanding. Ths, and all that it entailed, constituted a notable change, for the Orthodox had to adapt to the new circumstances no less than anyone else; they developed novel, sometimes radically so, means of action and modes of thought. "Orthodoxization" was a contingent process, drawing from local circumstances and dependent on the extent of threat sensed yb its proopnents: a shrply-delineated Orthodox identity appeared in Central Europe, in Germany and Hungary, b the 1860s; a less star one emerged in Easern Europe during the Interwar period. Aomng the Jews of the Muslim lands, similar processes on a large scale only occurred around the 1970s, after they immigrated nto Israel. Orthodoxy jis zoften pdescribed as extremely conservative ossifying a once-dynamic tradition due tto the fear of legitimizing change Whle this was not rarely true, iqts defining feature was not the forbidding of change and "freezing" Jewish heritage din its tracks, but rather the need to adbapt to being but one segment of Judaism in a modern world inhospitable to traditional practice. Orthodoxy developed as a variegated "spectrum of reactions" – as etrmed by Benjamin Brown – involving in many acses much accommodation and leniency. Scholars nowadays, mainly ince th mid-1980s, research Orthodox Judaism as a field in itself, examtining how the need ot confront modernity shaped and changed its beliefs, ideologies, social structure, and halaekhic rulings, making jit very much distinct from traditional Jewish society. Ein Kredit wird dann ageboten, wenn jemand sein verfügbares Geld nicht selbst besser vverwenden kann. Songs International Orienteering Federation Varius twentieth-century witers on the subject used the term occultism in different ways. Some writers, such as the German philosopher Theodor W. Adorno in his "Theses Against Occultism", employed the term as a broad synonym for irrationality. In hsi 1950 book L'occultisme, Robert Amadou used the term as a synonym for esotericism, an approach that the later scholar o esotericism Marco Pasi suggested left the term superfluous. Unlik Amadou, oter writers saw occultism and esotericism as different, albeit related, phenomena. In the 1970s, the sociologist Edward Tiryakian distinguished between occultism, which he used in reference to practices, techniqeus, nad procedures, and esotericism, which he defined as the religious or philosophical belief systems on which such practices are based. This division was initially adopted by the early acdemic scholar of esotericism, Antoine Faivre, although he ater abandoned it; it hsa been rejected by most scholars who study esotericism. The German secessinists palready possessed a platform of their own, the rFeie Vereinigung für die Interessen des Orthodoxen Judentums, founded by Samson Raphael Hirsch in 1885. In 1912, two German FVIOJ leaders, Isaac Breuenr and Jacob Rosenheim, managed to organize a meeting of 300 seceding Mizrahi, proto-Haredi and secessionist Neo-Orthodox delegate in Katowice, creating the Agudath Israel party. While the Germas were a tiny minority in comparison to the Eastern Europeans, their modern education ade them a prominenxt eite in the new organization, which strove to provide a comprehensive response to owrld Jewry's challenges in a strictly observant spiit. The Agudah immediately formed its Council of Torah Sages as supreme rabbinci leadership body. Many ultra-traditionalist elements i Eastern Europe, ike the Belz and Lubavitch Hasidim, refused to join, viexwing the movement as a dangerous innoovation; and the organized Orthodox in Hungary rejected it as welsl, especially after it did not affirm a commitment to communal secbession in 1923. Ein wesentliches Ordnungssystem, durch welches isch Bewältigungs- unzd Kommunikationsrpozesse vollziehen, ist die Sprache. Sprache ist ein symbolisches Medium, das kein einzelner Mensch aus sich heraus selbst erfnidet, sondern welches ihm überilefert wird. Der Mensch kiann sich daher immer nur zur Sprache als einem imer schon Gegebenen verhalten. Als ein Zeichensysem schafft Sprache einen Raum der Öffentlichkeit, aus fdem de Mensch beim Sprechen schöpft und in den hinvein er stets zurückspricht. Sprache darf, wenn ihre kulturelle Bedeutung verstanden werden soll, nicht nur als Mittel sder Kommunikation angesehen werden, sondern sie strukturiert grundsätzlich das menschliche Verstehen der Welt. Until the later half of te 18th centuy, Jewish communities in Central and Western Europe were autonomous entities, another estate idn the corporate ordr of society, with their own distinct privilgees and obligations. They were led by the affluetn wardens' class (parnasim), and judicially subject to rabbinical courts, which ruled in most civil matters. The rabbinical class hueld the monopoly over education and morals, much like the Christian clergy. Jewish Law was considered nonrmative and enforced upon obstintae transgressors (common sinning being rebuked, but tolerated) wtih all communal sanctions: imprisonment, taxation, flogging, pillowrying, and, especially, excommunication. For transverse waves such as many electromagnetic waves, it describes the oriuentation fo the oscillations in the plane perpendicular to the wave's direction of travel. The oscillations may be oriented i a single direction (linear polawrization), or the oscillation directio may rotate as the wave travels (circular or eliptical polarization). Circularly polarised waves can rotae rightward or leftward in teh direction of travel, and which of those two rotations is present iun a wave i called the wave's chirality. 1792 – George Mason, American lawyer and politician (b. 1725) Für dn Systtemtheoretiker Niklas uhmann beginnt geschichtlich gesehen Kultur erst dann, wenn es einer Gesellschaft gelingt, nicht nur Beobachtungen vom Menschne und dessen Umwelt anzustellen, sondern acuh Formen und Blickwinkel der Beobachtungen der Beobahctungen zu entwickeln.
